animal.description:
This 1 year old cutie is a good cuddler and an even better kisser. Meet Belle. She's ready to go home with you.

Belle was surrendered to MCR recently, and the volunteers and staff here have loved getting to know her. So far, we've learned that Belle loves to snuggle close to her people, enjoys food as much as we do, and has an adorable playful streak. We've also noticed how she thinks the outside world is pretty terrifying -- especially when there are loud noises or sudden movements -- so she'll need more help to build confidence.

Belle's previous family reports that she's good with older kids, other dogs, and cats (though she is a fan of giving big smooches to her kitty friends, which is not always well received). She was also housetrained but had started to go potty inside recently, so she'll need help re-learning that skill. 

In her previous home, Belle liked to wrestle and to play fetch, and when she was left unattended, she found other ways to entertain herself, like chewing. This lovely gal will need outlets for her mental and physical energy, and since Belle, like most dogs, really loves to chew, she'll need some good and safe options for putting her chompers to work. 

We think Belle would enjoy living in a home with another dog friend, particularly one who's confident and playful. And we know she'd appreciate having a human lap available to rest her head on at the end of a long, fun-filled day.
For more information about our adoptable dogs and/or to submit an adoption inquiry, please visit meridianrescue.org.
animal.name: Belle

animal.description: Onyx is a sweet, happy little girl. Since coming into foster, she has gotten accustomed to sleeping in a crate at night. She's also slowly learning commands including sit and touch (she is very food motivated). She's extremely gentle taking treats and is friendly toward everyone (people and dogs included). She enjoys spending her days lounging in the backyard, sunning herself to sleeping on the couch with another doggie companion. She also periodically enjoys playing with her fellow canine companion and in a couple instances, when she has gotten excited, she's even zoomed around a bit. She enjoys car rides and just about any adventure that has come her way. She is enthusiastic about taking walks and despite her physical ailment, she is able to keep up (she switches between walking and hopping along...which is very cute to see :) Overall, Onyx would be an ideal dog for a couple or family (with or without a canine companion) who enjoys easy activity/exercise.

animal.description: Shyla was brought into our shelter by Animal Control as a stray in July of 2019. Since that time, she has been adopted twice, and returned twice. Each time we have learned something different about this beautiful girl. And, we will not fail her again. Shyla must be the only pet and would prefer an adult only home, although she can do well with mature children over 12 who can respect her space. She desperately needs someone who will be her leader and help her to make the right decisions. An active person or family is a bonus, she loves exercise! With time and patience, her confidence will grow again, and she will become the good girl we know she can be. Shyla is currently working with a dog trainer to jumpstart her transition into your home.Call HSCC at (814)535-6116 for more information about the adoption process.

animal.description:
The world famous Carter is now looking for a great new home! Sadly, Carter didn't become famous for anything good. Carter's owners moved away to Georgia and left him chained up in the backyard with a bloody bandage wrapped around his injured neck. Carter spent many months under medical care receiving laser therapy on his severely infected neck and finally, he's all healed! Carter is a little less than a year old and this poor boy has never known what it's like to be in a home. Everything is new to him and many things scare him. Our staff have helped him in overcoming his fears, but Carter will need an experienced and patient home where he'll get all of the direction and attention he deserves. He's a sweet, affectionate boy that loves everyone he meets. He's learning to love toys and he loves to run laps around our exercise yard. Carter will need a home with no young kids or cats, but seems fine with larger dogs. He will need a fenced yard as well. If you can offer Carter the perfect home that he's so deserving of, call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org for an application and appointment. File#29895 11/20/20

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

Gunner is currently undergoing fast kill heartworm treatment.

animal.description: Meet Reyna! Reyna is a very sweet and active 3 year old Pit mix! Reyna is looking for an owner that has experience with dogs that need some training. Reyna probably never had a stable routine or anyone that worked too much with her, but you can tell that she wants to learn! She is a very smart girl and is very food motivated. All she wants to do is make you happy, but she may need some patience and a stearn voice to make sure she knows who the boss is! Reyna came to us quite starved of food, which has made her develop some guarding of high value treats and food. Simple fix to that, leave her alone while she eats! Reyna is a big sweetheart and just wants a chance at the loving life she so greatly deserves! She has not met any dogs here yet, but does seem like she might like a playmate. She would also probably do fine in a home with a cat. Reyna would do best in a home without young kids, but would probably enjoy older (13+) kids to play with. If you are interested in meeting Reyna, please fill out a questionnaire (either in person or online at gobroomecounty.com/shelter) and staff will contactvthose that seem to match the needs of Reyna! If you have further questions about Reyna, please call the shelter (607)778-2493 or email us at muttsrus@broomecounty.us.

animal.description:
MEET MOJO!!

Mojo is an incredible pup. There's something about his eye contact and facial expression that's just a little different than any other dog we've spent time with - it's like he can understand us when we speak. He's typically very playful, energetic and inquisitive, and loves to snuggle. He's very bright, and very trainable--we were able to teach sit and stay in just a few minutes, and his recall is also strong. Recently, we have realized that he's able to learn the names of his toys and distinguish between them and have been trying to build that vocabulary. He loves a romp in the yard and loves to chase a ball. Most of the day, though, he's content to relax and nap.

Mojo has issues with aggression that are problematic. Based on the trainers and behaviorists, it is clear that they are all fear-based aggression. (he's is not aggressive due to dominance). We were recently prescribed a drug (Clonodine) that enables him to walk outside comfortably (loose-leash and happy), but is reactive is people and dogs. He has an issue with resource guarding and has occasionally been reactive in the house. Mojo will need a person who is familiar with fear based aggression and reactivity. We know the right person is out that that can help this great dog.

If you are interested in meeting this dog, please visit our website for our online application www.underdogaz.com

PLEASE NOTE: This dog is courtesy posted for another individual or Rescue. Different policies and fees may apply.

animal.description:
Surely someone wants to get Busy!

This fabulously rambunctious and cuddly girl is quite the partner in crime. Busy is quite smart and has the skills to show for it. She knows basic commands such as come, sit, lie down and give a paw. She'll even put a paw on your shoulder if she feels you need some comforting. In her previous home, we were told that Busy has a high prey drive, which is all about management. Her keen sense of smell and likely some genetics mean that as her owner you will need to be vigilant when out on walks as she can sense a squirrel up a tree from miles away - and try to drag you along for the ride while she hunts it. Leash training here in shelter has been a successful work in progress and will likely need to be continued. 

She is selectively dog reactive, can get quite excited when she meets new people and has a low tolerance for loud overexcited groups of people or children. So maybe no other pets in the home, and no dog parks. She does have some food allergies and loves her Kirkland Salmon and sweet potato dry kibble. Please know that she may have some age on her, but if her prey drive takes over she can jump/climb 5-6 ft fence. Housing options will be up for discussion. 



Due to the current COVID-19 pandemic our adoption process has changed. 
Please visit our website for more information on the adoption process and to fill out an application. 

https://www.spca.bc.ca/adoption/how-to-adopt 

All adoptions are by appointment only once we have received an application.
***Due to the high number of applications we receive for our animals, we will only be contacting potential adopters to further review their application***
Thank you and we look forward to reviewing your application.

 Primary Color: White Secondary Color: Brown Weight: 27.2kg Age: 7yrs 8mths 1wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description:
Please contact Jo Ellen (hwbdogrescue@aol.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **
Aaron is an adorable 4-month-old Brussels Griffon blend who weighs approximately 9 pounds. Aaron is a very active puppy. He is highly intelligent and would benefit from a professional puppy training course. Aaron is a problem-solver and this can at times be to his determent as he is a flight risk and an escape artist. He absolutely must never be left unattended while outdoors as he can climb a low fence or dig under a fence. For these reasons, Aaron will not be placed in a home with children. Aaron can also be vocal when left alone and would not be a good match for the apartment lifestyle.
Please understand you are committing to providing a good home for his entire life (up to 15+ years or more) - not just until his puppy cuteness wears off.
You must be committed to housebreaking, age-appropriate enrichment and exercise, leash training, grooming needs, and positive socialization.
Like most puppies, he may chew on anything within his reach to include but not limited to baseboards, shoes, socks, children's toys, electrical cords, plants, etc.
His adoption fee is $300. This includes his neuter surgery, rabies vaccination, Nobivac Canine 1-DAPP vaccinations, Bravecto, Drontal Plus, Tri-Heart Plus Chewable Tablet, 24PetWatch microchip, leash and collar, and a trial offer for 24PetWatch Pet Insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.
Please ensure your application is complete before submitting. We do verify property ownership, landlord references, apartment/HOA restrictions, veterinary references, and criminal histories.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@gmail.com.
** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and adults dogs are tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and opportunity to enroll in a 30-day trial of pet insurance.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time from the Austin area.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
My name is Liam Neeson, and I'm even more handsome than my famous namesake. I'm probable more snuggly too, but I can't prove it! I am still learning about trust, and just like that other Liam, I don't like things being "Taken" from me. Because of this would do best in a home with experienced owners and no young children. Please check back for updates as my foster family gets to know me. You can also watch for stories, pictures, and videos about me on JR's Pups-N-Stuff's Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/groups/40103261297/. Ask to meet me today!!
 
Adoption fee: $425
 
Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.
 
All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.
 
Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab at JRsPupsNStuff.org. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.
 
JR's Pups-N-Stuff Dog Sellers License 270089-DS

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Daphne and Violet
=========================================================

Please contact
app@aarfhouston.org
for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .

Puppies
that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations.

Children under 8 years old
often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.

Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue!

The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

weight: 
estimated age: 

This dog recently arrived and is just settling in.  If you are interested in adopting, you MUST come in person during adoption hours and fill out an application.  Adoption hours and address are viewable on the website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org


---FAQ---

Is This Dog Currently Available?... This dog is available at the Small Miracles rescue facility in Ellicott City.  To submit an application, please come meet this dog in person.  You can bring your application with you, or you can fill one out when you come in.  Dogs will be removed from PetFinder only when they have an approved application or more than three (3) interested applicants.

Where did this dog come from?...  We rescue dogs from 100% kill shelters in West Virginia and on occasion from Kentucky.  On rare occasions we accept owner surrenders.  Due to the nature of the shelters they were rescued from, we often do not know the dogs' history.

How Old is this dog?...  We look at a dogs' teeth to estimate its age, and then the age is reevaluated by our veterinary staff when the dog is spayed/neutered.  If an age is not posted online, please feel free to inquire.

Is this dog Good With Kids?...  We occasionally know for sure if a dog is good with kids because it came from a home with kids.  This is rare.  We always suggest you bring your children in to meet the dog if you are seriously interested in adopting.  Dogs may like some kids and may dislike others.  Dogs are individuals, just like kids are.

Is this dog Housebroken?...  Advice from a veterinarian:  Even if a dog is housebroken at my house, it does not mean that it understands not to pee at someone else's house.  It ONLY understands not to pee at my house.  Some dogs make the connection that they should only pee outside.  Some must be retrained when they come home.  All we can tell you for sure is whether/or not a dog's crate is clean when we come to walk them in the AM.  All this means is that they are crate trained and waited to pee until we took them outside.

What is this dog's Temperament?...  We do not have a clear picture of a dog's temperament until we have allowed them to settle in for a few days.  Even then they are living in a shelter environment with many other dogs and a lot of daily activity.  It can be difficult to say a dog is "calm" or "nervous" when the shelter environment is playing a big role in that behavior.  We only rescue FRIENDLY dogs who have no known bite history.  If a dog is at Small Miracles, it likes people and has a good temperament.  We always suggest you meet the dog to see if it is the right fit for your lifestyle. 

What are your Fees?...  Base adoption fee is $325 for adult dogs and puppies.  To this, we add a $30 microchip fee, which we register for you, and a 6 month supply of heartworm preventative.  Heartworm preventative costs $40-60 depending on the weight of the dog.  This means that a large dog will total $405.00 and an extra large dog will total $415.00.

Why can't I adopt a FREE dog?...  Our adoption fee covers many procedures which cost much more for us then the amount we ask for from you. We spay/neuter all pets, and we give them their first round of vaccines (canine distemper, bordatella, Rabies if age appropriate).  At a typical vet clinic this would cost you $500 at minimum for the surgery, and each vaccine is roughly $35 each.  Even if your adopted dog does not have all of its shots due to the mandatory waiting period between booster shots, we offer vaccinations at the low cost of $20/shot.  We test all dogs for heartworm disease and tickborn illnesses such as Lymes.  We never euthanize a heartworm positive dog, and treatment routinely costs us $3000/dog.  We collect a fecal sample from every rescued dog and run a microscopic parasite test.  Any parasites found will be treated with two rounds of the appropriate dewormer.  We treat all dogs for fleas and ticks with Advantage.  If a dog has significant dental disease or "very dirty teeth", we will perform a dental cleaning when the dog has its spay/neuter surgery.  A dental cleaning with extractions would cost you upwards of $400-600 at your local vet clinic.

ALSO NOTE... Small Miracle is a 501(c)(3) charitable organization.  We survive off of our adoption fees and donations from the community.  We are a non-profit animal rescue and do not receive income from tax revenue as some county shelters do. 

For more information including Adoption Hours and Rescue Address, please visit our website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org

animal.description:
Mercedes is a super sweet senior of about 10 years old that has been waiting for what seems like forever for a great new home. She came to us in December, 2019, when her owner became homeless and could no longer care for Mercedes and older gal pal, Midnight. We tried for quite a while to get Mercedes and Midnight adopted together, assuming that they were very bonded, but it turns out that they could take or leave each other. Mercedes still has lots of energy at her age, and she seemed to be a bit much at times for Midnight. They can certainly be adopted together but they don't need to be. Aside from Midnight, Mercedes does not get along with other pets. She does, however, absolutely adore people, and she can't get enough attention. She's playful and active, and well-behaved too. Mercedes is housebroken and walks well on a leash, and no one will love you more than her if you give her a chance! File#29430 12/10/19 Call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org to meet Mercedes.

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

animal.description:
Vixen is a 6 ½ year old spayed black female with natural ears who came back into rescue through no fault of her own. She is currently in a foster home with no children or pets and is adjusting well. Vixen is a generally quiet and clean girl who loves her stuffies and fleece blankets. She is initially standoffish with people especial men. She has growled at a few men in and outside her previous home on occasion, but nothing aggressive. She travels very well and walks nicely on leash. She is a “beefy” girl who loves her food and treats. She is quite the talker, whiner, and a groaner especially when she thinks it is time to eat. She is pacing a lot but we expect that is just part of her transition process. Vixen is house trained and can be trusted with free run of the house when the foster parent is out. In her original home, Vixen lives with other Danes and her best buddy was a male. She had some exposure to barn cats there, but we are not sure if any of it was up close and personal. She was attacked by one of the female dogs in the house and since then has been female selective, so she would do best in a home with only male dogs. In her second home, she lived with teenage boys and guinea pigs. She was initially curios about the guinea pigs, but then just ignored them. She seems to have a high prey drive as she aggressively chases squirrels and neighbor’s cats when they are in her yard. Thus, she will not be placed with cats or small animals. Vixen is seeking a new permanent home that will help her feel secure and get back her girlish figure. Vixen came back to MAGDRL in January 2021 (2).



For more info on this dog and our adoption policies, visit PA MAGDRL at http://www.padanerescue.com. MAGDRL adopts Great Danes in NY, NJ, PA, MD, DE, DC, VA, & WV.

animal.description:
Yoda is a 9 month old female Retriever and Terrier mix. From her foster family - Meet Yoda!  She is a very sweet girl. She is great with other dogs and would do best with a canine companion in the household. She loves to play with toys and bones and is great with sharing.

Yoda is house trained and sleeps through the night. She is the perfect balanced dog you can go explore with or chill and watch a movie. She is nervous with people at first but she works through it quickly. The best fit for her would be somebody to encourage her through some of the nervous tendencies she has. She does great in the car and already knows sit and is working on down.

She would do best with older kids (age 12+) if any, because she does get nervous around loud noises . She needs a cheerleader to help her through and let her know she is alright and boost her confidence. Yoda loves to be warm and cuddle in blankets. She is looking for somebody to explore with.

 Want to Adopt? 1) Fill out an application on theluckypuppy.org The donation fees are minimum $475 for puppies up to 6 months, minimum $400 for dogs 7 months to 6 years and minimum $ 300 for 7+ years/Special Needs. 2) Once your application is in, our adoption coordinator will contact you and complete a vet check and home visit (possibly electronic). 3) Once approved, please schedule a meet and greet to see the dogs. Meet and greets are by appointment only for approved adopters.

Yoda is available in NY through the Go North Program of The Lucky Puppy Rescue centered in Bonifay and Panama City, FL (NY Lic #1054). This dog is in NY currently. The minimum donation $400 adoption fee includes transportation from FL to NY, spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, de-worm, flea prevention, heartworm prevention and martingale safety collar. Adoption fee payment methods accepted are credit, debit, Paypal and bank checks. No personal checks or cash. Applications must be submitted through our website - theluckypuppy.org - thank you! You may copy and paste the following link to apply: http://www.theluckypuppy.org/adoption-application/

***ADOPTION PENDING***

PLEASE READ THIS PROFILE AND THE REQUESTED CRITERIA BEFORE CALLING OR SUBMITTING AN APPLICATION. THANKS FOR YOUR ATTENTION AND CONSIDERATION 

MEET FITZGERALD….known to all his friends as “Fitz or Fitzy.”  This adorable, tri colored, 3 yr old, 12 lb Shih Tzu mix came from the SEAACA shelter when the person who was supposed to adopt him never showed up!  Lucky us!   Lucky Fitz!!  He had a small growth on the back of his neck, which we had removed.  He was a little slow to warm up — like 10 minutes and he was jumping into my arms!  He is very people oriented and we are currently fostering him with another dog to see if he would be happier with a canine companion or not.  He is a kissy face boy who loves his people and he will whine/cry for a few minutes when you leave him, so he doesn’t really like being left behind!  He seems to be potty trained or will go on a pad if he has to go out before you take him (but you know we never guarantee how he will be at your house!!).  He likes toys and still trying to figure out what to do with them!  He likes other dogs but is still a little shy and blossoming.  He would be fine with older kids (over 10 yrs) as he is very active and can scratch you when he jumps up on you (small children wouldn’t like that)!  Loves to go on his walks and meet other people on the street.  He is happy and playful…but we are still learning more about him.

We have only had him a short time, so please check back for updates.  HE WILL BE AVAILABLE FEBRUARY 15.

Our website is updated daily. Please do not apply for this dog unless your home fits the specified criteria. All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, groomed, vet checked, dewormed, deflea'd and come with a leash, collar and ID If you are interested in adopting this dog from Lhasa Happy Homes, please complete the adoption application via the link below: Adoption (Online) Application: https://lhasahappyhomes.org/adoptions/adoption-application/. We will contact you once it has been reviewed. 

During the COVID-19 quarantine, Lhasa Happy Homes will NOT be holding weekly adoption events. We will set up individual meet & greets with APPROVED applicants once they have submitted a video tour of their home. 

You can check our Events Calendar at http://www.lhasahappyhomes.org/HLM_Custom_Calendar.aspx.

Thanks for thinking rescue and adoption…and for considering saving a life. It will be the best gift you ever give yourself or your family.

This dog recently arrived and is just settling in.  If you are interested in adopting, you MUST come in person during adoption hours and fill out an application.  Adoption hours and address are viewable on the website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org


---FAQ---

Is This Dog Currently Available?... This dog is available at the Small Miracles rescue facility in Ellicott City.  To submit an application, please come meet this dog in person.  You can bring your application with you, or you can fill one out when you come in.  Dogs will be removed from PetFinder only when they have an approved application or more than three (3) interested applicants.

Where did this dog come from?...  We rescue dogs from 100% kill shelters in West Virginia and on occasion from Kentucky.  On rare occasions we accept owner surrenders.  Due to the nature of the shelters they were rescued from, we often do not know the dogs' history.

How Old is this dog?...  We look at a dogs' teeth to estimate its age, and then the age is reevaluated by our veterinary staff when the dog is spayed/neutered.  If an age is not posted online, please feel free to inquire.

Is this dog Good With Kids?...  We occasionally know for sure if a dog is good with kids because it came from a home with kids.  This is rare.  We always suggest you bring your children in to meet the dog if you are seriously interested in adopting.  Dogs may like some kids and may dislike others.  Dogs are individuals, just like kids are.

Is this dog Housebroken?...  Advice from a veterinarian:  Even if a dog is housebroken at my house, it does not mean that it understands not to pee at someone else's house.  It ONLY understands not to pee at my house.  Some dogs make the connection that they should only pee outside.  Some must be retrained when they come home.  All we can tell you for sure is whether/or not a dog's crate is clean when we come to walk them in the AM.  All this means is that they are crate trained and waited to pee until we took them outside.

What is this dog's Temperament?...  We do not have a clear picture of a dog's temperament until we have allowed them to settle in for a few days.  Even then they are living in a shelter environment with many other dogs and a lot of daily activity.  It can be difficult to say a dog is "calm" or "nervous" when the shelter environment is playing a big role in that behavior.  We only rescue FRIENDLY dogs who have no known bite history.  If a dog is at Small Miracles, it likes people and has a good temperament.  We always suggest you meet the dog to see if it is the right fit for your lifestyle. 

What are your Fees?...  Base adoption fee is $325 for adult dogs and puppies.  To this, we add a $30 microchip fee, which we register for you, and a 6 month supply of heartworm preventative.  Heartworm preventative costs $40-60 depending on the weight of the dog.  This means that a large dog will total $405.00 and an extra large dog will total $415.00.

Why can't I adopt a FREE dog?...  Our adoption fee covers many procedures which cost much more for us then the amount we ask for from you. We spay/neuter all pets, and we give them their first round of vaccines (canine distemper, bordatella, Rabies if age appropriate).  At a typical vet clinic this would cost you $500 at minimum for the surgery, and each vaccine is roughly $35 each.  Even if your adopted dog does not have all of its shots due to the mandatory waiting period between booster shots, we offer vaccinations at the low cost of $20/shot.  We test all dogs for heartworm disease and tickborn illnesses such as Lymes.  We never euthanize a heartworm positive dog, and treatment routinely costs us $3000/dog.  We collect a fecal sample from every rescued dog and run a microscopic parasite test.  Any parasites found will be treated with two rounds of the appropriate dewormer.  We treat all dogs for fleas and ticks with Advantage.  If a dog has significant dental disease or "very dirty teeth", we will perform a dental cleaning when the dog has its spay/neuter surgery.  A dental cleaning with extractions would cost you upwards of $400-600 at your local vet clinic.

ALSO NOTE... Small Miracle is a 501(c)(3) charitable organization.  We survive off of our adoption fees and donations from the community.  We are a non-profit animal rescue and do not receive income from tax revenue as some county shelters do. 

For more information including Adoption Hours and Rescue Address, please visit our website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org

**ADOPTIONS ARE BY APPOINTMENT ONLY WITH AN APPROVED ADOPTION APPLICATION. Please see our website for our adoption application at

https://homeatlasths.org/dog-adoption-application/

and information on the adoption process

Meet Joe! This old man was brought to HAL back in November after someone found  him abandoned on an old highway. He was covered in growths both small and large. Some even dangled several inches from his body making it uncomfortable for him to get around.  Since being at HAL Joe has had his much needed surgery to have his growths removed.  He is now happier and much more comfortable.  He has quite the pep in his step.  He is about 13 years old and we believe him to be a lab mix.  He keeps his kennel space clean which shows signs that he may be house trained. Although we always remind adopters that new surroundings can provide a slight learning curve in their new environment so accidents can happen. This old man would love a warm and comfy home to call his very own for the remainder of his golden years.  He doesn't seem to mind other dogs as long as they are older and his own speed slow, gentle and lazy ;) he has not paid any mind to the kitties here either.  If he goes to a home with children we recommend that they are older so that they are not to rambunctious for this sweet guy.  Joe's adoption fee is $125.00 this includes his neuter, utd on his vaccines, micro chipped, free vet visit within the first two weeks of adoption and free custom engraved ID tag.

animal.description:
George is a 6 ½ year old neutered fawn male with natural ears who came into rescue due to a divorce. He recently suffered some very traumatic events including a near-death experience shortly there after lost his older female Dane sister with whom he was very attached. Despite all of this, he is adjusting very well in his current foster home where he lives with a 5-year-old spayed female Dane and 5-year-old neutered Pitbull and proving to be a perfect gentleman. George is affectionate and playful, but also quiet and keeps to himself right now. He travels very well and walks very well on leash. George is housebroken and can be trusted to roam freely while the foster is out. George is good with children and other dogs. His only exposure to cats that we are aware of was in the home where he stayed a few days prior to coming in to rescue. The two older cats and George just looked at each other and the cats walked away. George came into MAGDRL in January 2021 (2).



For more info on this dog and our adoption policies, visit PA MAGDRL at http://www.padanerescue.com. MAGDRL adopts Great Danes in NY, NJ, PA, MD, DE, DC, VA, & WV.

animal.description:
Cody and Oreo were left orphaned when their dad passed away from COVID. 

Oreo (blk and tan) is a 12 year old Yorkipoo. He loves to wander around the house and is pretty independent. He isn't too snuggly, but we love watching him as he enjoys rolling around in blankets or on the carpet and he loves toys and food. 

Cody (white) is a 7 year old Maltese/Terrier mix. He is more shy, sensitive, and submissive. He follows Oreo wherever he goes. Cody doesn't want to get in anyone's way and even moves if someone tries to eat from his own food bowl! It took Cody a couple weeks to get comfortable enough to jump on the couch and snuggle with people, but he definitely does now! He just needs someone to give him time to adjust. 

Oreo is almost completely deaf and has slight vision loss but he doesn't have any issues getting around. Just don't expect him to come when he is called. He sleeps very soundly and snores a little at night. He just had bloodwork done which was totally normal and a dental so he is set for awhile.

They lived outside prior to coming to us so they are still being housebroken now. They are both crate trained (they sleep in same crate) and don't have accidents in there. When loose, Oreo does try to tell you when he has to pee by going to the door, but if you don't take him out right away, he does urinate inside. Cody is learning pretty quickly and is almost housebroken now. 

They both get along with other dogs and cats. They are neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. Cody and Oreo are beautiful, sweet dogs and would be a great pair to relax at home with!

 If interested in meeting, submit your applications now at www.dominoeffectanimalrescue.org!

animal.description:
Please contact JoEllen (sagdinfo@aol.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **
Aaron is an adorable 4-month-old Brussels Griffon blend who weighs approximately 9 pounds. Aaron is a very active puppy. He is highly intelligent and would benefit from a professional puppy training course. Aaron is a problem-solver and this can at times be to his determent as he is a flight risk and an escape artist. He absolutely must never be left unattended while outdoors as he can climb a low fence or dig under a fence. For these reasons, Aaron will not be placed in a home with children. Aaron can also be vocal when left alone and would not be a good match for the apartment lifestyle.
Please understand you are committing to providing a good home for his entire life (up to 15+ years or more) - not just until his puppy cuteness wears off.
You must be committed to housebreaking, age-appropriate enrichment and exercise, leash training, grooming needs, and positive socialization.
Like most puppies, he may chew on anything within his reach to include but not limited to baseboards, shoes, socks, children's toys, electrical cords, plants, etc.
His adoption fee is $300. This includes his neuter surgery, rabies vaccination, Nobivac Canine 1-DAPP vaccinations, Bravecto, Drontal Plus, Tri-Heart Plus Chewable Tablet, 24PetWatch microchip, leash and collar, and a trial offer for 24PetWatch Pet Insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.
Please ensure your application is complete before submitting. We do verify property ownership, landlord references, apartment/HOA restrictions, veterinary references, and criminal histories.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@gmail.com.
** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.

Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and opportunity to enroll in a 30-day trial of pet insurance.

Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved and you are traveling from out-of-town, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Hello. I’m Willa. I was brought in to the pound as a stray, so it was pretty scary and I kept close to my best friend at the time, Polly – she’s also looking for a new home, by the way. My foster mom says I’m a little shy but very loving. I like the company of other dogs but I’m a mellow girl. I’m good with children, I’m crate-trained and I walk well on the leash. I’m still working on figuring out the potty training at my foster mom’s place but everything is so new here still, so give me a little more time and I think I will get it and will be fine. I’m just a little slower with getting used to new environments. That’s why I’m hoping when you fall in love with me, I will get to stay with you forever.

If you are interested in meeting this pooch, please download the Adoption Questionnaire (farescue.org/pdf_files/questionnaire_canine.pdf), fill it out and email it back to us at info@farescue.org or fax (310) 362-0321. You can also meet this and/or other available dogs at our weekend adoptions.

[Willa is about 4 years old and weighs 12 lbs.]

animal.description:
weight: 
estimated age: 

This dog recently arrived and is just settling in.  If you are interested in adopting, you MUST come in person during adoption hours and fill out an application.  Adoption hours and address are viewable on the website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org


---FAQ---

Is This Dog Currently Available?... This dog is available at the Small Miracles rescue facility in Ellicott City.  To submit an application, please come meet this dog in person.  You can bring your application with you, or you can fill one out when you come in.  Dogs will be removed from PetFinder only when they have an approved application or more than three (3) interested applicants.

Where did this dog come from?...  We rescue dogs from 100% kill shelters in West Virginia and on occasion from Kentucky.  On rare occasions we accept owner surrenders.  Due to the nature of the shelters they were rescued from, we often do not know the dogs' history.

How Old is this dog?...  We look at a dogs' teeth to estimate its age, and then the age is reevaluated by our veterinary staff when the dog is spayed/neutered.  If an age is not posted online, please feel free to inquire.

Is this dog Good With Kids?...  We occasionally know for sure if a dog is good with kids because it came from a home with kids.  This is rare.  We always suggest you bring your children in to meet the dog if you are seriously interested in adopting.  Dogs may like some kids and may dislike others.  Dogs are individuals, just like kids are.

Is this dog Housebroken?...  Advice from a veterinarian:  Even if a dog is housebroken at my house, it does not mean that it understands not to pee at someone else's house.  It ONLY understands not to pee at my house.  Some dogs make the connection that they should only pee outside.  Some must be retrained when they come home.  All we can tell you for sure is whether/or not a dog's crate is clean when we come to walk them in the AM.  All this means is that they are crate trained and waited to pee until we took them outside.

What is this dog's Temperament?...  We do not have a clear picture of a dog's temperament until we have allowed them to settle in for a few days.  Even then they are living in a shelter environment with many other dogs and a lot of daily activity.  It can be difficult to say a dog is "calm" or "nervous" when the shelter environment is playing a big role in that behavior.  We only rescue FRIENDLY dogs who have no known bite history.  If a dog is at Small Miracles, it likes people and has a good temperament.  We always suggest you meet the dog to see if it is the right fit for your lifestyle. 

What are your Fees?...  Base adoption fee is $325 for adult dogs and puppies.  To this, we add a $30 microchip fee, which we register for you, and a 6 month supply of heartworm preventative.  Heartworm preventative costs $40-60 depending on the weight of the dog.  This means that a large dog will total $405.00 and an extra large dog will total $415.00.

Why can't I adopt a FREE dog?...  Our adoption fee covers many procedures which cost much more for us then the amount we ask for from you. We spay/neuter all pets, and we give them their first round of vaccines (canine distemper, bordatella, Rabies if age appropriate).  At a typical vet clinic this would cost you $500 at minimum for the surgery, and each vaccine is roughly $35 each.  Even if your adopted dog does not have all of its shots due to the mandatory waiting period between booster shots, we offer vaccinations at the low cost of $20/shot.  We test all dogs for heartworm disease and tickborn illnesses such as Lymes.  We never euthanize a heartworm positive dog, and treatment routinely costs us $3000/dog.  We collect a fecal sample from every rescued dog and run a microscopic parasite test.  Any parasites found will be treated with two rounds of the appropriate dewormer.  We treat all dogs for fleas and ticks with Advantage.  If a dog has significant dental disease or "very dirty teeth", we will perform a dental cleaning when the dog has its spay/neuter surgery.  A dental cleaning with extractions would cost you upwards of $400-600 at your local vet clinic.

ALSO NOTE... Small Miracle is a 501(c)(3) charitable organization.  We survive off of our adoption fees and donations from the community.  We are a non-profit animal rescue and do not receive income from tax revenue as some county shelters do. 

For more information including Adoption Hours and Rescue Address, please visit our website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org

animal.description:
Hello, meet tiny Licorice. She is an honorary Great Pyrenees, disguised as a one-year-old, seven-pound, Maltese and Shih Tzu mix. She was rescued by the Great Pyrenees Rescue Society from a Texas animal shelter as an owner surrender.

Licorice is a sweet girl who requires a lot of love, attention, and patient. She likes to snuggle and is content being close to her person. She is okay with cats and is good with other dogs.

She will thrive in an adult-only home, and older, considerate children may be okay. She would require a canine companion her size. She needs members in her family that will treasure her for the rest of her life. Please complete an Adoption Application if you are that family or person. She is only available for adoption in OR and WA.

PUPPIES ARE ONLY PLACED IN HOMES WITH YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL RESIDENT DOGS.

Our requirements for puppy adoption are simple and necessary.

	Our puppies are not livestock guardians, they are family pets that live inside the family home.
	Puppies must be placed in homes with a youthful, adult resident dog of similar size. This gives the puppy a mentor and a solid foundation for becoming part of the family.
	Puppies are only adopted to homes with someone at home at least part of the day. If no one is home for 6-8 hours at a time, please do not apply.
	Preference is always given to those with Great Pyrenees experience.
	Applicants must have secure, visible fencing and a socialization plan in place.
	The fastest way to be considered for a puppy is to fill out an application. Adoption is not first come, first served. GPRS and its fosters work diligently to find the right fit for each and every unique dog and puppy.

Adoption Fee $450 (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org .

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

animal.description:
Hi everyone! My name is Doodle, and I am about 12 years old, and a little girl at about 13 lbs. I am a sweet girl, very calm, and I love giving lots of kisses! I just need lots and lots of love. I am house trained. I am a very chill baby, and just love to snuggle and follow my humans around. I need a home with no stairs, a solid fence, and without a pool, to keep me safe, since I cannot see or hear very well now, and my joints prefer solid ground! I am very well-behaved, and am looking for a home where I can relax, snuggle, and get lots of love! My adoption fee is $75, but if you are a senior human over 65, my adoption fee is waived. If you are interested in any of our Boston Terriers or would like to be eligible to adopt a Boston Terrier through our rescue in the future, please fill out an application. It can be found at www.texasbostons.com. Click on the Rescue tab and then on the Adopt Now! tab. Here you will find our adoption requirements along with a link for an online adoption application. This will allow you to get on our list of approved homes so you can immediately adopt a Boston Terrier when it becomes available through Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas.

We are always looking for good foster homes. These homes allow us to rescue more Boston Terriers in need because we have a place for them to go until they are adopted. This will allow you to possibly become a foster home for one of our little Boston Terriers in need. Thank you for considering the possibility of fostering for Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas!

Any and all Donations are always needed and welcome. Because BTRNT is a 501(c) 3, all donations are tax deductible. If you wish to donate to Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas, please go to www.texasbostons.com and click on the red "Donate Now" tab at the top left of the page. If you wish to donate dog food or any other item, please mail to:

Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas

Plano, TX 75086

If you have any questions regarding Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas please call 844-428-7776 and leave a message. Your call will be returned as soon as possible.

Thank you for your continued support in our rescue efforts! Help us Rescue The Bostons!

animal.description:
Posted: 01/30/21

Molly is a 7 1/2 yr old sweetie who looks like a Lab mix. She is spayed, microchipped and up to date on shots. She is a skinny 50 lbs and may fill out to about 55 or so.

Molly was surrendered when her owner could no longer take care of her.  Molly was diagnosed with exocrine  pancreatic insufficient, EPI.  Her pancreas does not create the enzymes to digest her food and provide her body with nutrients. We are happy to report that she is doing well taking pancreatic enzymes will every meal, her prescription diet.  If it sounds expensive, it is.  

Molly is eating Science Diet ID - Low Fat, both kibble and canned with a little pumpkin puree on top.  Each meal needs to prepped with her prescription pancreatic enzymes.  They are mixed in her meal and take 15-20 minutes to start working.  We are doing this 3 times a day with great success.  Three meals a day and EPI warrant a number of bathroom breaks,  Molly is housebroken and lets me know when she has to go out, even at 4 am!

Molly is worth it!  She is living with four other dogs and loves to cuddle with her foster family.  She is sweet, sensitive, and playful.  She loves to play with the other dogs in the fenced in yard, toss around her stuffed toys, and get pet whenever she can.  She walks pretty well on leash and is always so excited to go out. We have noticed that she takes a number of visits to get comfortable around new men and warms up to women quite easily.

I feed her separately from the other dogs.  While she does not guard her food from people, she does not like other dogs around her food.  My vet told me that this is not uncommon with EPI dogs.  Three meals a day has helped from getting overly hungry during the day.


Molly needs someone who is home often to maintain her three meals a day and bathroom breaks. Plus, I am estimated the monthly cost of her meds and special diet to be between $550 - $700/month.  She cannot go a day without her medication and plant-based alternatives will not work.

Molly's adoption fee is $300. She is being fostered in Cambridge, MA and Newry, ME.

WANT TO ADOPT MOLLY?
Please copy and paste the following URL into your browser to complete an application. http://alldogrescue.org/adoptable-dogs/adoption-application/

Molly's foster mom will be in touch within 48 hours of receipt of your application.

animal.description:
Hello! Thank you for checking out Phi's listing. Please read carefully for details on our adoption process:
•First, please note that we are unable to receive correspondence through Petfinder’s system. Any messages sent through Petfinder or any buttons on this listing will unfortunately not reach us. If you’re interested in adopting please visit www.sanctuaryrescue.com and submit an adoption questionnaire under the forms section.
• Applications for puppies are open for two to three days in order to give ample opportunity to prospective adopters. At the end of this 48-72 hour period we will change the adoption listing to “Applications Closed”. At this point we will begin reviewing all applications received. Next, foster parents will contact approved applicants to set up a meet and greet. This can take up to 1 to 2 weeks.
• Once a dog is officially adopted we will remove its listing from Petfinder. So if this listing is gone, this dog has found its forever family and is no longer available.
• Since Covid lockdown orders, we have seen a massive increase in people interested in adopting dogs (yay!). This means each dog, especially puppies, receive multiple applications in the couple of days we have applications open. There is usually several applicants for one puppy. If it doesn’t work out this time, please understand this is not a personal judgement but likely a result of supply and demand. We encourage you to reapply in the future.

This lucky puppy found his way to the home of a Sanctuary Rescue foster with mom and siblings at just one day old. Mom is a beautiful, 50pound-ish, black lab-looking mix. We never met dad so breed and size is a pure guess. We estimate he'll be in the 60-70 pound range when full grown. Phi spends his time wrestling with the other pups in the house, lounging around the house, playing tug and just enjoying some good old puppy fun. Phi is well socialized and love everyone they meet. He is young enough to learn about cats.

This is Phi. He is a sweet little guy that LOVES attention. He loves to ruff house, carry around sticks around the yard and likes to play with kids and other dogs.

Phi's adoption fee is $295, which includes age-appropriate vaccinations, neuter, and microchip. If you would like to make this handsome pup a part of your family, please visit sanctuaryrescue.com and complete an adoption questionnaire under the “Forms” tab.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Breanna,

I am a very loving, sweet girl of 10 months and 60 pounds. A gentle fella raised me and I have been loved on a lot. I have no clue that I am a pit bull. Some of us get a bad rap, because people think pit bull fighting is great sport. Really ,watching an animal attack another is fun? I am so glad no one expected that of me. I am one big baby, that has never had a bad day. I am happy and very loyal to my people. I was living in an apartment complex and took the elevator to the outdoors. I am now on freedom farm and run out the dog door when ever I want. I went from city to country. My owner could not take me with him, when he moved out of the apartment. I was so lucky to move into the rescue. I am great with dogs and love to play. I am fine with all people, children and dogs. I have not met a cat yet. I am house trained and can be trusted loose, when left alone.I am pretty much a perfect girl. I love to give kisses and be loved on. I could be the poster child for pit bulls. It is all how we are raised. We are great dogs, when not with the wrong owner. For those people that fight us to make money, all I have to say is -get a job. I am here waiting for you to make me the center of your world and you will be mine. Isn't that what all of us dogs of all breeds want? Hugs and kisses.....

If interested, you can easily fill out an adoption application by clicking here:

adoption application

For anyone viewing this on Petfinder, if you are interested in adopting this animal you will need to go to our website www.rosesrescue.net to fill out the online adoption application. You can usually find more pictures of the animals there too. Click on our name "Roses Rescue" in blue above to be taken directly to our website.

animal.description:
Three sisters and a brother! Sounds like the title of a TV show. Darla, Darcy, Dani, and their brother Daren make an awesome litter according to their foster mom. They are 3-month-old mixes of Plott Hound and Shepherd weighing only 15 puppy pounds but heading to a mature weight of about 50. Short coats of brown brindle set them apart from many other dogs; they love being held like a baby and having a good tummy scratch! Each is loving and sweet with an overall excellent temperament which clearly shows when they're around people and other dogs. A truly awesome litter! Their foster knows what she's talking about! (posted 1/29/21, ME)
**It is rare that we know with certainty the ages or mixes that make up our dogs, but we do our best to be as accurate as possible based upon our experience. **
Adoption: $350 which covers quarantine, shots, worming, food, medical records, spaying/neutering,microchip and an Alabama State Health Certificate.
Transport, if needed : $140.00 We consider the transport to be of great importance and, as such, take particular care of the dogs during the trip from Alabama. We make every effort to arrive with healthy and minimally stressed dogs.

This tiny guy was rescued from a high kill shelter along with several other pups after their owner was no longer able to care for them. Wrinkles can usually be found cuddled up with his canine buddies or snuggling on the couch with his foster mom. He is great with other dogs and seems to enjoy the companionship of his canine pals. Please help us find Wrinkles the forever home he's been dreaming of!

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Seven - yup, just like the number, lucky number Seven! I'm such a happy and friendly 53 pound pup! I love going for long walks in nature or around the neighborhood -- the longest we've walked was on a 7 mile trail. I do great on car rides too. I stay in my seat for the whole ride and either snooze or put my head as close to my foster mom as I can and stare at her until she can give me pets. I'm still just a baby so everything is very interesting to me, but a treat really grabs my focus fast I'm a quick learner too -- I already know how to sit, stay, wait, and come. I'm good on a leash and don't have much interest in other creatures, like other dogs, squirrels, deer, or little humans, Sometimes, I get too excited when I'm playing and I use my mouth more than I should and it's hard for me to tell where the toy ends and my human begins. My foster mom and I have been working on that, but it's harder than it looks and I'd love to continue practicing this with my new family. I don't bark, the only time my foster mom heard me bark was when I saw my reflection in the mirror, but once I realized it was me, I've found that looking in the mirror is fun! I snore during my naps and like to make grunting sounds (my foster mom sometimes calls me Mr. Pig) but I'm usually a very quiet pal. I've had some play dates with other dogs, too, and they've been really fun but they always get tired faster than I do. 

One of my favorite things to do is cuddle. I love being as close to my human as possible, so if you sit down next to me I'll immediately wiggle my way over and snuggle my head (and sometimes my whole body) right into your lap. I can stay like that for hours! I have plenty of love and snuggles to share but my high-energy is too much sometimes for even me to contain, so I don't think I'll work well with small humans, but having another dog buddy around could help me manage my energy and help with my focus. 

For more info, or to meet me virtually, contact AdoptSeven@gmail.com.
animal.name: Seven

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Burrito! I am an 4 year old, 5.5lb chihuahua and totally adorable.

I have special needs and am paralyzed in my back legs. I can drag my legs behind me and get around okay, but I do best in my wheelchair. A home with no steps would be super cool. I LOVE my person (my foster mom right now)...and admit that I didn't have a good attitude when I was at the vet. They called me a little landshark! Lol... so, if you can be a little patient and let me make sure you are safe, we will do okay.

Oh, o

ne more thing. I am not "potty trained" but am able to hold my pee and poop until it just surprises me and comes out (kinda like it's ready to come out, but I don't know). Totally pooped on my foster mom a few days ago... but she was nice about it and cleaned me up. Uhm... and full disclosure, I was getting in her bed and peed while dragging myself over her pillow... that was a first. I normally sleep through the night without accidents. Clean sheets and sweet dreams!

Thank you for checking out my bio, please check back for an update. My life was saved recently and we are getting me safe and warm. Information will be updated as soon as I get settled in at my foster home.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online. http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

animal.description:
PLEASE before you email us with any questions PLEASE visit our official website directly for more information and availability of our dogs. www.arizonacattledogrescue.org

The first step to meeting any of our dogs is to submit an application. It in no way obligates you to adopt, it is simply part of our process. If the dog you are interested in is adopted before you can meet them or if we do not currently have a dog you are interested in we still encourage you to go through the approval process. Then you will be pre-approved and ready to adopt when a dog does come along that you are interested in. Apply at www.arizonacattledogrescue.org

Julio is a stunningly beautiful boy who came to us a year ago. He is just over a year old now. He was adopted and then returned due to a family issue and through no fault of his own.

He is a very sweet boy who is quite sensitive. He LOVES other dogs and would excel in a home with another dog to help bolster his confidence. He would also do well as an only pup in the house if given stability and direction.

Julio is looking for someone who will have a little patience in gaining his trust. 

He loves being outdoors. Older kids are recommended for Julio and we are unsure regarding interaction with cats. He did live the last few weeks with a tiny pug puppy and was very gentle with it.

Male

Hi my name is PJ! You may remember my sad intake picture (see comments). I did not come from a place that took care of me or showed me what love was. The nice people at the shelter have made me nice and healthy and they are learning more and more about me every day. I am a very affectionate boy who loves to give hugs and kisses. I have a pittie wiggle down! I LOVE playing fetch. I get along with most dogs but like to meet my friend companions before hand.
I was in a very nice foster home for a bit but sadly I had to come back to the shelter because I was a little too territorial of my person and her property. I wanted to protect her from all the bad in the world, because that is all I have ever known. I hope to find a home that will work with me on this issue and keep me secure if new people come to the home until I realize they are okay. I promise I want to learn. I am VERY SMART.

You can meet PJ 1pm-4pm at 3016 Milam Dr. Brownwood, Texas 76801
(325) 646-0617

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Online Adoption Application 

My name is Snoop Dog or Snoopy. I'm a fun goofy boy. I'm good with cats and other dogs. It does take time for me to warm up and become comfortable in new places. I was found under a trailer and was pretty skinny from not eating well. Since I've been with my foster mom she has been introducing me to people the correct way since I'm a little nervous at first. I've been doing really good with new people since I know not all people are going to hurt me. I've started gaining weight and am starting to look and act like more like the puppy. I'm affraid I'm not going to get my next meal so I do like to guard my food so I need to be fed alone or in a low trafficked of the home and preferably a home with no young children. I'm very smart I have already learned to sit and wait for my foster mom to put the food bowl down for me. She loves me very much but she wants me to find the perfect forever home!!
Foster Mom Note: Since he is nervous around new people I instuct them to not touch him right away, to let him get a feel for them first and since I've been doing that he has improved with greeting.

Snoopy
has been in our Dash/Prison training program where he has learned most of his basic commands.

animal.description:
Hi, Im Gizmo. I am an almost 2-year-old Rat Terrier, and I weigh around 19 pounds. I had a bit of a rough start in my life, but my foster mom tells me things will only get better. I am having some trouble with my right eye. Its either injured or infected, which may cause me to end up with a permanent wink. Can you find it in your heart to love me, even if I only have one eye? I promise it doesnt stop me from being a sweet, pretty girl!
 
I do very well with other dogs. It can take me a little time to warm up, but I take cues very well and quickly figure out my place in the pack. I enjoy playing with other dogs and with squeaky toys! However, Im not sure if I like cats or not.
My foster mom is SUPER proud of me because I have not had one single accident in the house! I use the doggie door and do all of my business outside. I also do well in a crate - but ever since Ive settled into my foster home, I dont spend much time there anymore. Even when mom leaves us dogs alone in the house for a while, I wait patiently until she returns.
 
My favorite pastime is cuddling, but Im happy to faithfully sit close-by and wait for your attention. I have a good appetite, and I am quite athletic. I love spending time outside. Whenever one of my foster brothers or sisters goes out, Im always the first to join them. Plus, my foster mom thinks I have been very helpful scaring off moles in the backyard, so Ive been earning my keep!
animal.name: Gizmo

animal.description:
The Bug Buggy is a one year old American Staffordshire Terrier mix who was dealt a rough hand in her first year of life. With untreated glaucoma in her left eye, it was far too damaged to be saved and had to be removed. But, you cant squash this Bug! She is recovering excellently and becoming more confident every day.

As a professional napper who dabbles in slow walks and wet kisses, Bug loves nothing more than to lay by your side. If you give this girl a toy, she will collect it by putting it in her toy pile or just lay her head on it until she feels satisfied. Bug is dog friendly, good with cats, walks well on a leash, and crate trained. She is mostly housebroken with regular outings and requires only a short walk a day to be happy. I believe she would love to live with a doggy companion to show her the joys of being a family pet.

Anyone looking for a mellow girl and a pal for their current dog(s) should meet this awesome little pirate pup.

BONUS: Buggy is also and overnight viral TikTok star!

animal.description:
Hercules is a Rottweiler mix, one-year old, about 80-85 lbs, came to us from an owner who had taken him on and just had too many dogs to be adding a very large dog to the mix. He is supposed to be housetrained, good with other dogs & seems to be ok with cats; unsure about children. He is very playful, loves balls and squeeky toys, loves having his tummy rubbed, stayed in a fence and walks well on a leash.
DOG ADOPTION FEE is $100. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more. (If a dog is sponsored or has a waived or lower fee, that info will be provided at the point of adoption to the approved adopter).
The first step is to our Adoption Application here: https://elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html .
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
To learn more about us, visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org; Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description: SHAYLA came to us from a southern california shelter. She found herself on the road to being euthanized and was listed as rescue only. SHAYLA is a high energy, high prey drive dig, which can be a wonderful thing if it is soemthing you know how to work with. Some of our smartest dogs are high drive dogs and SHAYLA is no exception. She is very food motivated which makes training her very easy and fun to do, but her biggest challenge is laying down and relaxing. She does work on her place command several days a week and is getting much better at calming down but she will need continued training and an owner excited to work with her. SHAYLA is very pretty and sweet with humans, she is crate training and potty trained. SHAYLA is great dog she just needs to find a human that is up to her standards. SHAYLA will still need to be spayed before her adoption can be offically but she is looking for her forever home.

animal.description:
Meet Mystery! The name fits because no one knows her exact age or breed, but we can say that she's about eleven years old, 13 lbs and some type of Terrier mix, and a full-bred heart melter! Mystery is probably also part dragon since she has these cute wispy mouth whiskers and a puffy snoot. Her dragon powers include mind-controlling her humans to cuddle and give her unlimited treats! She's definitely earned those treats, because even at eleven, she has already learned new tricks like walking on a leash, how to sit, high five, and beg. Her favorite activity is snuggling up with her blanket and special human on the couch to binge your favorite Netflix series until you both fall asleep. She's super gentle and loves kids, other dogs, and cats. We promise you will fall in love with this sweet girl!

One this to know about Mystery is that has seizures and needs medication for it. But it's very easy to manage - just two pills a day, that she'll gladly gobble up with her breakfast and dinner. But the doctor prescribed one more thing: a bunch of love! She's such a sweet love bug and would need a home willing to take their time to get to know her. She's quite shy, since in her earlier years she was found as a stray, but with enough love and patience (and maybe a few extra treats) she'll gladly call you her favorite hooman.

Do you want to be Mystery's forever home and give her all the love she deserves? Put your application in today!

If you are interested in adopting, please visit the I.C.A.R.E. Dog Rescue website and complete an adoption application: www.icaredogrescue.org/ready-to-adopt

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter shots up to date micro-chip fecal and vet checkClick here to watch a video of Mystery.

animal.description:
0121096

I need a single family home with a fenced in yard since I require lots of physical and mental stimulation!

Meet Brle!

Quite possibly the sweetest and most delightful puppy alive, Brle surpasses all expectations. This wee lady is beyond adorable, super smart, curious, playful, and snuggly.

At roughly 15 weeks on 1/20, she weighed in at 18.5lbs. Shes definitely put on a couple pounds since joining her foster family. Shes doing great with potty training, pretty consistently going outside if the door is open or on puppy pads if not. She knows sit, no, treat, and food, for sure. And she has not been exposed to children or cats.

Brle loves treats, toys, exploring, being outside, all people and dogs shes been exposed to, watching the wild turkeys, wrestling with her youngest canine foster brother, giving kisses, and stealing her fosters slippers to snuggle with.

She does NOT like being alone. Brle is a social creature. She is very attached to her foster and canine foster siblings. When contained in a crate or behind a doggie door she will cry constantly. If crated within eyesight of her foster human, however, shes perfectly fine and quiet.

As such, her foster feels very strongly that shed do best in a home both with another dog and with at least one human who is home the majority of the time (long-term, NOT just during COVID).

Additionally, this wee lady is going to be athletic and fairly high energya prime adventure buddy. Her foster would definitely not recommend a sedentary home. Her brief forays on leash around her fosters property indicate that Brle will be an excellent hiking companion or trail running friend once shes old enough. 

As a husky mix, she can certainly be vocal, but really only when joining the pack in excitement over a deer sighting or a FedEx deliveryand when left alone/confined alone. Otherwise shes not much of a barker. She is a loud sleeper though! Lots of snores and interactive dreaming. Its very cute.

Whomever adopts this girl is lucky indeed. The sweetness is overwhelming.

Webster came to DCCR with the many homeless dogs rescued from TX. He is being treated for heart worm (non contagious & DCCR pays for his treatment!). He likes to take short walks & spend LOTS of his time snuggling on a dog bed or soft blanket, so a low to medium activity house would be ideal, especially while hes taking his heart worm medicine.

Hi my name is Ferra. I am a rambunctious 5 month old mix. My foster mom thinks I might be a pitbull or boxer, she says just look at that block head! And she says I have the cutest head wrinkles too! I like telling my foster mom when something doesnt seem quite right, sometimes when people walk in the room or I see that scary thing called a vacuum I cant help but bark. I enjoy playing tug and keep away with my brother and foster sisters. I can be a little possessive of the toy I am playing with. I like to run around all the furniture. Once I am worn out I like to snuggle up with the big dogs on their beds or the sofa with my foster parents and cuddle. I like tummy and ear rubs but dont like my tail touched too much, my foster mom thinks it got hurt when I was really little. I am learning no bite but since Im a puppy I learn with my mouth and like to chew things. I have my big girl teeth though, so Im almost done teething. I think bones, squeekies and stuffies are awesome! I am house trained and go to the door when I have to potty, the big dogs helped teach me that! I sleep all night in my crate, and dont cry at all. Im a pretty smart girl and learned sit, shake, come and no already. My foster mom whistles at me and it really gets my attention. I sometimes like to stand up on my foster parents legs, but Im learning down. We are working on drop it but I can be a little stubborn sometimes. My foster mom took me for a walk on our street and she said I was such a good girl, it was exciting. I love treats, my foster mom calls them cookies. Oh, and I make the cutest sound when I yawn! I am going to grow up to be a big, strong girl and would love a home where I can run and play, go on adventures and at the end of the day give all my cuddles.
