Violeta is truly one of the sweetest girls ever and has melts everyones heart when they meet her! Whoever brings this amazing girl home will be so, so, so lucky. The petite pointer/ lab mix would cuddle with you on the couch all day if allowed. Her tail never stops wagging on walks and shes very serious about having her head down and smelling her path the entire time. She is attached to her humans will be your shadow around the home, get as close to you on the couch as possible, and lovessss to be petted and kissed. Shes gained the nickname snor-lax cause she has the cutest little snore while she naps. Shes also gained some weight since coming in to our house and its obvious getting food wasnt a sure thing before. She was a bit shy at first, but does trust every human shes met right away. Were working on jumping up to say hi, but shes so light, that some dont even notice shes doing it. She is 3 yrs old and definitely a mama before.

She would be the best addition to a home where people are going to be home and love on her, as she gets sad when her people leave. She doesnt pay much attention to the other dog in our house, but weve seen shes still learning how to truly play with other dogs, especially if they are very rambunctious. We think shed do just fine with another dog, but will just need time to learn how to play nicely, as shes probably use to fending for herself and does like a calm environment where she can relax. 

She quickly learned how to run on a leash, but we dont think shed prefer to do really hard hikes or go camping in the cold. (Shes from Texas so we understand.)

She is already such a good girl and learning house rules she didnt know when she came in (not to eat other peoples food, how to use a doggy door) and getting so much better at not barking at walkers and to not jump up on the counter even if she smells her food. Shes slept in her crate every night but she would just really really love if she could sleep on the bed or couch.

animal.description:
1220091

I need a single family home since I seem to be part pittie! I can NOT go to a home in a city or county with pitbull restrictions!

Hi my name is Fable. I am an inquisitive 5 month old mix. My foster mom thinks I might be a pitbull or boxer and that I might have been the runt of the litter since Im a lot smaller than my sister Farra, and I learned a little slower. I am a fairly shy boy, and tend to flop over with my tail between my legs when I see new people because I get nervous. I bark at new dogs and can be a little selective, so a slow introduction would be good. I enjoy playing tug and keep away with my sister and foster sisters. I like to run around all the furniture, sometimes when Im feeling brave I will pretend to be a mountain goat on the sofa. Once I am worn out I like to snuggle up with the big dogs on their beds or the sofa with my foster parents and cuddle. I like tummy and ear rubs a lot. I am learning no bite but since Im a puppy I learn with my mouth and like to chew things. When my foster mom says ouch or no bite I give her lots of kisses to say Im sorry. I have my big boy teeth though, so Im almost done teething. I think bones, squeekies and stuffies are awesome! I am house trained and go to the door when I have to potty, the big dogs helped teach me that! I sleep all night in my crate, and dont cry at all. Im a pretty smart boy and learned sit, shake, come and no already. I sometimes like to stand up on my foster parents legs, but Im learning down. We are working on drop it but I can be a little stubborn sometimes. My foster mom took me for a walk on our street and she said I was such a good boy, it was exciting! Now when I see the leash I really want to go explore the world. I love getting treats, my foster mom calls them cookies. I am a super shiny and handsome boy, and would love a home where I can run and play, go on adventures and at the end of the day give all my snuggles and kisses!

animal.description:
Summer -Female
Pointer/Terrier Mix (Breed is best guess only) 
DOB 11/29/2020
Current weight 7lbs

Meet Summer. Her mom and siblings were owner surrendered to the shelter when they were just 1 week old. A wonderful foster family took them in and now they are ready to find their forever homes. Though they resemble a Pointer mix due to coloring (it’s just a best guess) mom we were told is a schnauzer/terrier mix around 25lbs. She has been around other dogs, kids (age 13-2) and a cat. She’s working on basic puppy manners and is doing very well. She will need someone home most of the time so she can continue her potty training and socialization skills. If your gone more then a few hours, please consider an adult. Are you her forever home? If she could be, please fill out an adoption application on our website www.forevehomedogrescueil.org

WE DO NOT DO OUT OF STATE ADOPTIONS
Thank you for considering the adoption of one of our rescue dogs.  We are committed to finding our rescues the perfect home. Together we can make a difference in the life of a dog.
 
The adoption process should be a fun and exciting time for families and dogs. Our goal is to place our babies in forever homes.  The potential adopter needs to be dedicated to their care and training for life. 
Understand that sharing your life with a dog can be a commitment of 15+ years. This would include feeding, exercise, training, vetting, and providing a loving home. Ask yourself, "Am I ready for this type of commitment?"  If you are ready, we are here to help.  We do have some requirements to help us find the perfect placement of our babies. 

WE ARE A FOSTER BASED RESCUE ONLY. WE DO NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL BUILDING
1.  Apply online at https://www.foreverhomedogrescueil.org
We must have an application, conduct a phone interview, and meet your entire family (including other dogs) to approve an adoption. Only a final approval for adoption can take place after a successful meet and greet. This is done by appointments only. We will not proceed with the adoption if everyone has not met the dog.  This will allow others the opportunity to adopt the dog.
2.  Adopters MUST be 21 years old.
Information on all adults/members living in the home is required
We REQUIRE you to provide proof and vet reference that all current and past pets have been kept up to date on all routine medical.
3.  Illinois law requires that all of our dogs and puppies be spayed/neutered within 30 days of adoption. In order to fully comply with this regulation and reduce the number of homeless dogs and puppies, 
4.  If you do not own your home, you must provide landlord contact information on the application and a copy of your lease that outlines the rules for dog ownership in your residence.  
Large breed dogs will not be adopted into apartment settings or where there are breed/ size restrictions.
Puppies have special needs and require a home where someone is available to care for, socialize, and give basic training.  If you are gone for more than a couple hours at a time, please consider adopting a teen or older dog.
5.  Adoption fees are $350. We accept checks or cash. (Prices are subject to change without notice).
6.  All dogs and puppies adopted through Forever Home are fully vetted with age appropriate vaccines. Keep in mind once you take possession of your newly adopted dog, any and all future medical costs or care is YOUR responsibility.
7. First time puppy/dog adopters will be required to sign up for and pay in advance a basic training class. A deposit of an extra 50.00 will be required until a class has been completed, it will then be returned. 
8. WE DO NOT DO OUT OF STATE ADOPTIONS 
 
Medical included is as follows:
Spay/Neuter (age appropriate) *Forever Home uses Fox Valley Animal Welfare League in Aurora, IL
Age appropriate core vaccines
Fecal testing and deworming
Flea and tick preventative
Free 1st Vet visit at one of our participating vets
Microchipping
 
Forever Home Dog Rescue reserves the right to deny any applicant.

Labrador Retrievers are the #1 Favorite Dog Breed in America. Freddy is an excellent example of a Lab and Catahoula mix. He is the perfect all-around family pet for any family.
Freddy has thick soft sable fur with unique white markings. He is inquisitive, friendly and soooo handsome and playful. Freddie is people-oriented and very trainable. He will make you laugh and feel good and fill your Life with Joy. As an adult we foresee he will present a commanding presence!
Freddy and his siblings were born around December 9th to a smaller-sized (approx 40-45 lbs) Labrador Retriever mix mother and a Catahoula father. The puppies were left behind when their elderly owner was hospitalized. His granddaughter rescued the puppies to find them good homes. Freddy came to us in a good condition. He received his first set of puppy vaccinations and dewormer. On 01/29, Freddy weighed 8.2-lbs.
Freddy is looking for his Fur-ever home - Is That YOU? EMAIL us for more information about the adoption process and to SCHEDULE a time to meet this Handsome Boy! Thank you for seeking to adopt a rescued dog! :)

animal.description:
Tammy needs a home with: 
- no apartments, condos or townhomes
- no kids under the age of 10
- no other pets (would not do well at dog parks or with visiting dogs)

Adopt Tammy! Tammy is an adorable Shepherd/Lab mix with a dark coat and adorable up-ears. Tammy is a senior gal who we suspect is about 9-10 years old. Tammy is a big gal as well- weighing in at 94 pounds! This sweet lady wants nothing more than to be right by your side. She is very loving and will lean her whole body against you for pets and snuggles. Tammy is very snuggly and loves being up next to you on the couch or curled up on a dog bed at your feet. Tammy is house trained and an easy-going house guest. She rides well in the car too! Tammy knows how to sit and shake and she takes treats very gently. Tammy is looking for a loving retirement home (no apartments, condos or townhomes please) in which to live out her golden years. She would do best in a home with no to other pets and with kids over the age of 10. Tammy loves being with her people and can be very stressed when left alone. She would love a family who is home often and can take her along on car rides so she doesn't have to be left alone. Like most senior dogs, Tammy has some arthritis and joint discomfort in her hind end so she is currently on joint supplements and medication to help with inflammation. If you think Tammy would be the perfect addition to your family, submit an adoption application for her today! 

If you're interested in adopting Tammy, please email a completed adoption application to adoptions@kitsap-humane.org. Adoption applications and more information about our adoption process can be found on our website here: https://www.kitsap-humane.org/adopt/how-to-adopt/. Once your application has been received, you will be placed in line to have your application reviewed. All applicants are pre-screened over the phone, and then are scheduled for a time to come in and meet the dog at the shelter.
 Primary Color: Brown Weight: 81.2lbs Age: 9yrs 2mths 0wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description:
All dogs listed as on HOLD are NOT available for viewing by the public, unless you are their owner. 
Once a dog is no longer on HOLD, it is able to be viewed by the public, participate in meet & greets, and be adopted!

Adoption cost per dog is $99.00 (puppies under 6 months of age are $150.00). The adoption fee includes the following: OH license good for this calendar year, DA2PP, Bordetella vaccine, Heartworm testing, dewormer, and spay/neuter.  Flea treatment will be provided if fleas are noticed.  All dogs will be spayed/neutered and microchipped before leaving the facility.  An e-collar may be purchased for $15.00.  Because most of our dogs were picked up as strays, we have no knowledge of any behavior or health issues.  Stray dogs are held for 72 hours so that the owners have a chance to redeem them. After that time they are vetted and placed up for adoption. We welcome and encourage the cross posting of our dog's pictures to increase adoptions.

animal.description:
Buddy
2 years old
Female

Buddy is shy here in the shelter, and is rather stoic when meeting new people. She is slow to warm up, but worth the wait! She has lived with children in the past and done well with them, but due to her shy nature we feel that she should be placed with kids 15+. 

Buddy is selective with other dogs, she does well with calm companions. 
Buddy has previously lived with cats, and it can be managed. She will chase cats, but has not hurt any in the past. 

Buddy can be a vocal girl, and would do best in a house rather than an apartment. 

We always recommend crate training, exercise, playtime, and a regular schedule for potty breaks when bringing a new dog into your home. The shelter environment is much different than your home, so expect the unexpected. We do our best to help find the right pet for you, but your new dog may act differently on your turf than he/she did on ours. Adjustment takes time for both you and your new family member, so remember to be patient and enjoy this new and exciting time!
Included in the adoption fee are rabies (if applicable) & distemper vaccinations, heartworm testing, deworming, spay or neuter surgery.

animal.description:
Diamond is a 2 year old pittie mix looking for a calm, mature family. She has been shuffled around from home to home, and needs someone experienced, patient, and willing to give her a stable and steady routine. She does take a little bit to warm up to new people, but once she knows you, she is very loving and cuddly. She is very loyal, and once comfortable, will be protective of her people and home.

Diamond's ideal home will NOT include any children, animals, or a high volume of visitors. When properly introduced, she can do well with new people, but should not be subjected to strangers continually coming and going. She will need a quiet, adult only home, a fenced in yard, plenty of chew toys (to keep her mind busy), and most importantly, patience and understanding. 

She is easily excitable, and does not know how to handle her excitement, which can result in her becoming mouthy. Her foster parents have been working with her to find ways to calm her when she does become excited, and Diamond has been doing GREAT! She really enjoys games that involve working for food/treats (such as hiding food, or freezing in Kongs), and would love her forever home to continue doing those things for her!

She is crate trained, potty trained, and knows sit, and shake. She would benefit from continuing her learning, and using her brain to advance her skills.

Interested? Great! Submit an application at www.caninecastawaysrescue.org. The application approval process can take up to 7 business days. Once approved, we will contact you for the highly anticipated meet and greet.

Not ready to commit to being a full time fur mommy or daddy? You can apply to foster! Just fill out the foster application on our website, and be very thorough so we can match you with a great fit for you and your home!

To meet Gunner or to be added to his waitlist, call (505) 983-4309 x 1610 and leave a voicemail message that includes the PUPPY'S NAME, plus YOUR NAME and A GOOD PHONE NUMBER - OR e-mail this information to adoption@sfhumanesociety.org. animal.description: Dear Santa, I'm Frankie, a handsome and friendly blue-eyed 2 year old, 50 pound Pit Bull Terrier mix! Could you and the elves make some phone calls to a bunch of dog-loving families and ask them to come to the shelter? I have been good with other dogs here. We all want to be HOME for the HOLIDAYS! I'm hoping to be able to leave you a big plate of cookies by my new fireplace.. Love, Frankie OKC Animal Welfare is open for adoptions from 12-5:30, 7 days a week. If you want to become a foster parent, fill out our application here: https://volgistics.com/ex/portal.dll/ap?ap=6848568 The dog/cat adoption fee, which is normally $60 unless we are having a special, includes spay or neuter, MICROCHIP, age-appropriate shots and health check. The shelter is at 2811 S.E. 29th St., phone # 297-3100. Use pet's ID # when inquiring. Special Adoption Fees: In the following cases, the adoption fee is $30-if more than one pet is adopted, if the pet is 4 years of age or older, if the pet has been in the adoption center more than 2 weeks, and if the pet is a 'special needs' pet.

animal.description: Woof, woof! I'm so excited you're thinking about adopting a new fur-ever family member! Here are a few things that may help you with your big decision. First, dogs just want to be happy and feel loved. Living inside and being a part of the family is really important to us. A lot of the things you need as humans to stay happy and healthy, us dogs need too. We depend on you for things like vet visits, nutritious food, clean water, social and play time with people and other pets, training classes, toys, and of course, lots of love and attention! Regular baths, nail trims and grooming help us to look and feel our best, while monthly flea and heartworm prevention help us to stay healthy. Did you know that depending on our size and breed, dogs can live up to 20 years? Just think of the wonderful life we could have together!

animal.description:
PIPER came to us from Oakland Animal Shelter. She was owner surrendered to them, stating she had been involved in a altercation with another dog outside her home. The story is that she broke out of her backyard, being protective of her puppies and attacked a person or dog that was walking past her home. OAS does not totally believe this story because there was no report filed or pictures taken against PIPER. OAS could not adopt her out because of this accusation and therefore she needed to go to rescue. 
Since PIPER has been in our care she has been an extremely easy dog to take care of. She is very quiet and crate trained. She is not reactive to the other dogs in our care and handles hanging out with them very well. She can be a bit wild and doing zoomies outside but inside she lives to snuggle. She is very quiet and gentle. PIPER still needs to be spayed before she can be adopted but she is actively looking for her forever home. Her chart from OAS states that she is 8 years old but we will be taking her to the vet soon to confirm this, PIPER seems to be a lot younger than that.

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Bernard and I'm a 2 year old, neutered, Pointer mix that currently weighs about 46lbs! I'm a high energy guy that would do best with an experienced family that lives an active lifestyle. I may thrive in dog sports like agility, tracking, or rally as a way to work out my energy and help me focus on training. I can be overwhelming for young children so I prefer a household with children that are 8 years or older that have lived with high energy dogs like me before. If there are dogs in the home, they should be tolerant of my outgoing personality and ideally be around my size. Please be sure to bring in the entire household, including any resident dogs, to meet me before I officially join your family.
If you are interested in meeting with me, please submit your fully completed Adoption Profile Form to adoptinquire@peninsulahumanesociety.org and an adoption counselor will call you to conduct a phone interview before making an appointment to meet in person. You must be 18 or older to submit an application. Please make sure to include in the application that you are interested in meeting me, Bernard ID# A888788.
Application: https://phs-spca.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/AdoptionProfiles_dog.pdfUnless otherwise indicated, adoptable animals are located at our Lantos Center for Compassion at 1450 Rollins Road, Burlingame, CA 94010. Please note at this time we are doing adoptions by appointments only. Please call us at 650-340-7022 to schedule an appointment.Our hours are weekdays from 11am-6pm and weekends from 11am-5pm (closed major holidays). Interested adopters must arrive at least 1 hour before close. We do our best to update our listings regularly, but we can't guarantee every animal you see is still available. It's also typical for us to have animals who haven't had their photos taken yet, so you are welcome to visit our adoption center and have a look around!
To check on an animal's adoption status, please call 650-340-7022 during normal business hours to speak with an adoption counselor. Emails will be returned as soon as possible, but please allow up to 48 hours during busy adoption periods like weekends.

animal.description:
***PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO & ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE CONTACTING ODR OR APPLYING FOR ADOPTION, THANKS!***


MEET Mondo -

Mondo is a 14 month old, short hair black & tan, 16 lb tweenie puppy.  Would consider placing with a sweet, gentle, younger, small non-alpha female dachshund (no male dogs), but no cats and please no kids (he is frightened of children). He's a typical happy go lucky doxie pup, loves to play, and is currently working on leash training. Mondo is a super handsome dachshund, very good breeding, just a happy/heathy little lad! Doxie saavy only please apply. Adoption fee: $595.

Mondo will do best in a family with a stay at home parent (work from home or retired) and only older children (over age 12), who are familiar with the special needs of Dachshunds.

Like all Dachshunds, Mondo is high energy and enjoys playing and warming his little bones in the sunshine, so along with regular walks around his neighborhood, Mondo needs a secure fenced yard to run around and explore safely. While small in stature, doxies are big on personality and don't generally do well in apartments, with all of the noises and traffic that come with multiple dwellings in a confined space.  To best set up our doxies and their new families for success, ODR, Inc., adopt to families who live in single family homes with secure fenced yards.

OUR CRITERIA (aka The Fine Print):

Based on 30 years of experience with rescue doxies, we have pretty strict criteria. Do you work from home/stay at home/work part time?  Have a securely fenced yard? We do not place same gender dogs in a home unless they were raised together, and children need to be 12 or older (some exceptions IF the dog is a puppy or the child has been raised with a doxie). We prefer non smokers and a home with no other small animals (ferrets, hamsters, etc). Cats are on a case by case basis depending on the dog. Remember, these are rescues; many were surrendered because of these issues. 

WHAT YOU GET IN RETURN WITH YOUR LITTLE RESCUE:

All our dogs are fully vetted, including spay/neuter, rabies, DHPP, Bordetella, Pyrantyl, nails trimmed, and dental when needed. They'll come with a basket of goodies, food, toys and a custom made harness. The adoption fee is $595, sorry no exceptions, as this covers the cost to rescue them, vet them and take care of them while in our rescue. It also helps towards the care of other doxies that come with huge vet or dental bills or need extensive behavioral training.

Can you give Mondo a happy, carefree life again? If interested, please complete the adoption questionnaire at www.odr-inc.org and email it to: jrangan@comcast.net 
The adoption committee will attempt to be in contact with you within 48-72 hours. Please be patient as we are solely volunteer run.

animal.description: TUG was owner surrendered to us at no fault of his own. TUG (from what we were told) lived with another female dog or several years. Him and the other female dog got in fights a couple time over food. His owners then began feeding them separately. Until one day they decided that feeding them separately was too much work. TUG and the other female dog then got in to another fight (there is a photo of what he looked like after coming out of the vet) and his owners took him to the vet to be euthanized. The vet did not feel comfortable putting TUG to sleep so they reached out to rescue for help. We then stepped up to save TUG's life. Since TUG has been in our care he has shown no aggression towards other dogs. We do feed our dogs separately, as most dogs should be but he is crated in a room full of other dogs where he eats with them and I have seen absolutely no negative reaction towards any other dog from him. He is a very sweet old man. While he is older, his spirit is very young and playful. He does the cutest spins when coming in and out of his crate or when its food time. He is currently being fostered in San Jose, CA and his foster says he is extremely easy and sweet to have in her home. When she has people come to her home, he gently greets them and then goes back to his bed to lay down. TUG would be a great addition to any home. He did previously live with young children but we have no idea how his interactions were with those children.

animal.description:
Trapezium was surrendered to Stockton Animal Services by her owner along with 9 siblings and her mother. The family was transferred to Valley Humane on 12/31. Trapezium weighs 14.4 pounds.

Trapezium will be available for adoption on Tuesday 2/2. Approved applicants will have the opportunity to meet the litter and choose their puppy. The first approved adopter will have choice of 10, the second will have choice of 9, etc. These puppies are not available to adopt in pairs.

The puppies appear to be a mix of working breeds. Mom appears to be a German Shepherd Dog mix (weighing 67#). The puppies are active and friendly. They are prone to nipping and herding and will benefit from puppy socialization classes.

During shelter-in-place, Valley Humane is conducting adoptions by appointment only. If you would like to adopt Trapezium or a littermate, please complete an Adoption Inquiry Form (copy and paste the following URL into your browser), https://valleyhumane.org/adoption/adoption-inquiry-form/

An adoption counselor will reach out via telephone to conduct an adoption interview. Once you have submitted your application, stand by to answer our call! Applicants will be interviewed on Saturday 1/30 or Monday 2/1.

If approved, we will schedule an adoption appointment for you and your family at our facility in Pleasanton on Tuesday 2/2.

https://valleyhumane.org/safe-adoption-guidelines/

animal.description:
*Needs another young confident dog* Needs a yard*Meet Tobias - the most gentle, mellow, and loving soul you will ever meet! He is a stunning one-year-old Spaniel/Pointer mix weighing about 25 lbs. He was recently found as a stray but now is living in a loving foster home. He is so well mannered at home and does great with everyone and everything. He wins over the hearts of everyone he meets with his gentle touch and laying his head down in your hands. Tobias constantly makes his foster family laugh with his giddy attitude while prancing around and wagging his tail (well really his whole bottom wiggles). He loves to be your shadow and will follow you around the house and will always lay next to your feet or curl up right beside you. Tobias loves the mornings and does the cutest happy dance when he sees his people are awake and it's time for a walk. He is happiest when with his person or other playful dogs, adores going on walks, and is absolutely the most easy-going dog we have ever met.

Tobias loves all humans, and although hasn't met young kids yet we think with proper supervision he would be great with them too due to his easy-going and mellow nature. With a slow introduction, Tobias does great with other dogs and once comfortable then wants to non-stop play. He has been living with two cats and does well with them too, only trying to play with them. He is now figuring out how to play with toys, and being reinforced with his house potty-training (and doing really well at it!).

Tobias' ideal home would have another playful/confident dog for him to follow and play with. It would also be great for his caretaker to be home often and/or work from home (even after the pandemic) as he loves to be by your side as much as he can. A home with a yard is preferred for him too, so that he has space to play with his new dog friend. Want to be his forever family? Get your application in today!

If you are interested in adopting, please visit the I.C.A.R.E. Dog Rescue website and complete an adoption application: www.icaredogrescue.org/ready-to-adopt

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter shots up to date micro-chip fecal and vet check

animal.description:
***PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO & ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE CONTACTING ODR OR APPLYING FOR ADOPTION, THANKS!***


MEET Tootsie -  

Tootsie is a 5.5 year old, 12 lb, AKC chocolate smooth hair dachshund. Cute as can be, just adorable with a very sweet disposition. Will consider placing with a gentle non-alpha male dachshund, but no kids and no cats. She loves her toys and likes to dress up. This is one special girl that loves her walks, but also loves to cuddle at movie time! Doxie savvy only please apply. If you want to adopt sweet Tootsie please fill out an application today! 

Tootsie will do best in a family with a stay at home parent (work from home or retired) and only older children (over age 12), who are familiar with the special needs of Dachshunds.

Like all Dachshunds, Tootsie is high energy and enjoys playing and warming her little bones in the sunshine, so along with regular walks around her neighborhood, Tootsie needs a secure fenced yard to run around and explore safely. While small in stature, doxies are big on personality and don't generally do well in apartments, with all of the noises and traffic that come with multiple dwellings in a confined space. To best set up our doxies and their new families for success, ODR, Inc., adopt to families who live in single family homes with secure fenced yards.

OUR CRITERIA (aka The Fine Print):

Based on 30 years of experience with rescue doxies, we have pretty strict criteria. Do you work from home/stay at home/work part time? Have a securely fenced yard? We do not place same gender dogs in a home unless they were raised together, and children need to be 12 or older (some exceptions IF the dog is a puppy or the child has been raised with a doxie). We prefer non smokers and a home with no other small animals (ferrets, hamsters, etc). Cats are on a case by case basis depending on the dog. Remember, these are rescues; many were surrendered because of these issues. 

WHAT YOU GET IN RETURN WITH YOUR LITTLE RESCUE:

All our dogs are fully vetted, including spay/neuter, rabies, DHPP, Bordetella, Pyrantyl, nails trimmed, and dental when needed. They'll come with a basket of goodies, food, toys and a custom made harness. The adoption fee is $495, sorry no exceptions, as this covers the cost to rescue them, vet them and take care of them while in our rescue.  It also helps towards the care of other doxies that come with huge vet or dental bills or need extensive behavioral training.

Can you give Tootsie a happy, carefree life that she deserves?   If interested, please complete the adoption questionnaire at www.odr-inc.org and email it to:  jrangan@comcast.net.  The adoption committee will attempt to be in touch with you within 48 -72 hours. Please be patient as we are solely volunteer run.
animal.name: Tootsie

animal.description:
We have a litter of 4 purebred Jack Russell Terriers for adoption. They were born on 12/2 . We rescued them from a backyard breeder who had them outside. They were laying on some cedar shavings in a shed with no heat, no blanket or anything. They were freezing. At first, we took a doghouse out there with blankets as the breeder/owner refused to let them inside. However, they started to get a rash and irritated skin on parts of their body (we suspect from the cedar chips) and they just looked miserable. The temperature at night was supposed to get down to 12 degrees , and we feared they would not survive another night of freezing temperatures, therefore, we ended up making an offer and buying the litter so we could get them medical attention, vaccinations, and find them wonderful homes. They are now safe in a warm home and bed, their rashes are healing, they are healthy puppies.

Mom is a 12-pound JRT and dad is 15 pounds. These cute little puppies are called Shorty Jacks because they have the short legs and longer body. The breeder docked the tails on 3 of them and one was born with no tail. They have had their first vaccines, have been dewormed, and microchipped. They are loveable and playful puppies, all of them. We have 4 females. They are also litter box trained. 

We require a fenced in back yard (physical fence) and our policy is no small children under the age of 7. Puppies needs a home where a primary adult caretaker is home during the day. If you have other dogs, another small dog 15 pounds and under in the home is acceptable, however no large dogs. 

Adoption fee is $425. They will be spayed before adoption, and they will be ready to leave on 2/14

Please put in an application on our website www.indianasaveadog.com A $50 deposit (once your application is approved) will hold your puppy until adoption day.

animal.description:
MEET GIZELLE!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. She is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A3840415.

Beautiful Gizelle was an owner surrender to the shelter and she is not handling shelter life well. She is so confused and doesn't understand why she isn't in her home anymore. Her previous owners stated that Gizelle loves her people once she gets to know them. She loves squeaky/stuffed toys and loved to sleep with her owners in their bed at night.

Now she just doesn't know where she is. She is scared and skittish when the shelter staff comes to take her out of her kennel. She is getting better with leash training and will even go for a short walk with the staff. She liked doing "zoomies" in the yard. She tolerates petting but doesn't seek attention. She is losing weight at the shelter and needs to get out soon.

Gizelle needs an adopter that understands she is going to need time and patience to get used to new people and a new home. She needs to be in a home where she is the only dog and any children should be 12+ years old. If you think you can give this big, beautiful girl the home she needs, please come and meet her today!

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

To actually visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
Did someone say the word "play?" 

Because Chance heard it. 

This active Boxer mix is around 2 years old and loves to have fun. He enjoys running around a yard with his foster brother who is a smaller dog, or bringing toys to you in the house to play fetch. (He's still confused why he has to let the toys go before they can be thrown again though.)

Chance is new to the leash and would need some guidance and patience to learn to walk on it without pulling. Fortunately he thrives on praise and loves food treats so teaching him commands hasn't been too difficult so far.

Chance is extremely people friendly and will beg for ear scratches after meeting someone for more than 5 minutes. While he gets along well with dogs, he will give an alert bark if he sees an unfamiliar dog nearby. He has not been tested with cats.

He is house trained and crate trained, though he does take a bit longer to settle down if he doesn't have a crated canine friend nearby. 

Chance is UTD on shots, preventative, micro-chipped, and neutered!

Chance 's adoption fee is $250, and adopters must live within 175 miles of the Quad City Area.

If interested in meeting Chance you must fill out the online application at www.k9kindnessrescue.org/adopt/application

Chance and K9 Kindness Rescue thank you for considering adoption through rescue for your new family companion!

Please email info@HWHANIMALRESCUE.COM for questions or to see our rules and to download the Required Application www.hwhanimalrescue.com

Jill is an approx 4 year old, 23lb beagle/hound mix. She is a beautiful girl with big sweet eyes who loves everyone she meets. Jill is a true pack dog, like most beagles, and would do best in a home with another dog and a fenced yard. She is very submissive with other dogs (and people) and loves to spend time cuddled up with her foster dog siblings or running around the yard with them. If it were up to Jill she’d also ALWAYS have a toy in her mouth. She adores stuffed toys and makes the cutest high pitched squeal when you give her one. Jill is almost potty trained but does still have an occasional accident in the house. She also has beagle energy and would do best with someone who will have the time to train her and give her lots of play and walk time. Jill is also crate trained when her foster family leaves the house and likes to sleep curled up next to her humans at night. 

Heart-worm negative, current on vaccines.  If not already spayed/neutered - it is included in adoption fee.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THIS DESCRIPTION THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING FURTHER ABOUT THIS DOG.  IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN APPLYING TO ADOPT, PLEASE DO NOT REPLY VIA PETFINDER, INSTEAD GO TO  www.arizonapoodlerescue.org TO THE “Adopt Me” SECTION TO FIND OUR ONLINE APPLICATION.  WE WILL NOT ADOPT OUR DOGS OUT OF STATE.   PLEASE RESPECT OUR PROCESS AND OUR TIME AS WE ARE ALL VOLUNTEERS.  WE WILL BE GLAD TO ANSWER QUESTIONS ABOUT THIS DOG ONCE WE HAVE AN APPLICATION IN HAND.  PLEASE NO PHONE CALLS! 

Monte is a 1-2 year old Chihuahua mixed with maybe Rat Terrier. He weighs about 12 lbs.  He is a fun wild child once you get to know him and he you.  He is shy with new people and would benefit from having a dog savvy Mom or Dad that will continue our work socializing him and make him feel safe with all humans. He will also need help encouraging him to continue in his housebreaking. On the fun side - he is a player.  He loves other playful dogs and will keep any young resident dog moving a lot of the day.  He is a ball dog.   Then he sleeps like a baby right next to them as the picture shows.  He will snuggle with his human too.  Monte can run like the wind is not much of a barker unless a stranger comes into his space.  Monte is a good little boy, would make a great addition to a family with adults and older children.  He might be fearful of loud active younger children.

There is an application and possible home visit or reference check prior to adoption.   Applications can be found on our website www.arizonapoodlerescue.org.   Click on the "Adopt Me" tab.    Monte is being fostered in Chandler.  His adoption fee is $200.

Arizona Poodle Rescue is an all volunteer non-profit organization.  We do not have a shelter.  Our dogs are currently being fostered in private homes generally located in the Phoenix and Tucson area.

animal.description:
Snoopy is seriously the best. He is like 80lbs of pure mush baby! He is still a young thing, too, so he may grow! But he actually will likely lose weight since he came to us slightly out of shape. Lots of jelly rolls!
We rescued Snoopy from The Anticruelty Society downtown and we are thrilled that we did. He was surrendered because his owner fell on hard times. 
Snoopy has more of a lab personality. He is congenial, friendly, waggy, and very calm in the car- a real pro!

Snoopy enjoyed his time in play group off-leash meeting a dozen dogs! His videos should be posted in this profile! He was the life of the party. He was the same with dogs as he is with humans, happy to see all!
He is just a super friendly, super happy, and lovely amazing dog. Can't say enough!

Snoopy has been in a foster home with a single girl in her apartment in the city and this is what she has to say about him:

"Snoopy aka Pike loves snuggles on the couch, your personal space, all toys and bones, and long walks around the park. He's a super social guy and loves to be around people. What he does not like is not being allowed on the couch, loud noises, people taking his toys away!

He is housebroken and he is getting there with the crate training. We are working on it. He had only been crated when I'm in the shower and we just started overnight crating. He whines for about 20 minutes but then settles down. He does fantastic after that, no barking or being destructive. I do give him a bone while he's in there to keep him occupied.

On walks, he pulls a little and we've been working on that. He's a close walker too. And I trip over him most of the time! When we cross paths with other dogs he's mostly just curious but never barks or lunges. He likes other dogs and people for sure. 

Pike is puppy-like with his toys. He loves anything he can chew! He's been great with flavored bones that are edible. With his plastic toys and stuffed toys you have to watch him because he rips whatever he can get off. He's destroyed stuffed toys and plastic toys but is great with ropes!

The important thing to know about Pike is that he is an excited nipper like a mouthy young pup, he doesn't mean anything by it except that he is happy, and he stops quickly, but would not be ideal for young kids. Once he calms down he's great. 
He also guards his toys. He's fine if you take his food away but don't touch the toys! He's easily distracted though with a treat and we've been working on fetch with sit and he drops the toy so he doesn't get snippy. A treat trade is key with this guy, and he has never gotten mean but we don't push it, I respect his choices and work around them by not pulling things out f his mouth and instead offering him a treat so that he drops his toy, which he does.

Overall, this guy is the sweetest! He's a bit tubby but there's more of him to love. He has been adjusting great to his new environment and just wants to cuddle. He's very curious in a puppy way. He loves to meet new people and has loved everyone he's met so far. He even gets compliments on walks. 

We tried to work on "no dogs on the couch", but he wasn't having any part of that! He does respond great to get off the couch though. Ha But I would love to see him in a forever home that will let him up on one because he is not a fan of the floor.

He loves his treats and will do anything for them. I think he purposely messes tricks up sometimes so he can get double treats! He's got sit and lay down, off the couch, and we've been working on stay, come, and go to your kennel. He's super quiet and whisper barks at you to get your attention. When he does bark, he's got such a deep voice! 

He gets the zoomies in the yard but tries to dig. He even likes to eat sticks. He's not a jumper, he needs a boost getting into my jeep. Not sure if it's because he's tubby, or he doesn't know how. But he does great with the 4' fence. He's not a fan of loud noises, but if they're consistent, he adjusts to them. For example, he doesn't like the construction noise, but learns to ignore the people that live above us. 

He's been great with only chewing his own toys and doesn't try to chew furniture or clothes or shoes. He's easily occupied with a bone that lasts a long time. Otherwise he loses interest in toys unless you're playing. He's a sweet boy who just wants lots of love."

We think Snoopy would be a great companion for a variety of homes given his good nature, we just wouldn't place him with young children. He is really the best boy so we hope you will apply today as his foster mom would love to tell you more!

Do you have room in your heart and home for adorable Atlas? He's a soft and fluffy baby - only 14-weeks-old and he already weighs 45 pounds! His foster mom says he's a bit shy and mostly a lap dog who wants to be adored and cuddled. We are still working on his house training so an adopter will have to be prepared to help him with that along with learning how to walk on a leash. He still hasn't had all of his shots so will need to wait till he does to go on walks. He enjoys toys and playtime with the foster family's young dog. Atlas has a good appetite and he will likely weigh more than 100 pounds when full grown. He will do well with a spacious yard and someone that has experience with large dogs. He is neutered, microchipped, and current on vaccines. If you're interested in Atlas, an application is absolutely required. You can submit an application by clicking on the APPLY FOR ADOPTION button or by pasting the following into your browser.
https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/TVAR/Dog
Because we expect an outpouring of interest in Atlas, we are not able to respond to numerous inquiries and emails. We are looking for the right match for Atlas given his size and breed and if you don't hear from us within a week, please assume he has been adopted.

animal.description:
Ruby is a 2.5 year old Boxer mix, full of fun and energy! She loves the outdoors, and spending time with her human. If you're looking for a hiking partner or running partner, look no further!

Ruby has been a support dog for a veteran for the last 9 months. She is very obedient and attentive to whoever she claims as her human. She takes a bit to warm up to new people, and will require several meetings with potential adopters. She has been shuffled around from home to home since a pup, so she just needs some stability.

She walks well on leash, is crate trained, potty trained, muzzle trained. She needs, and thrives, with structure and routine! She is treat motivated, a quick learner, and is always up for an adventure with her person.

Ruby needs a home WITHOUT other animals and kids.  

Her dislikes/triggers: direct eye contact, sharing food/toys, baby talk.

Ruby's perfect person would continue working with her on obedience, and keep her on a routine so she can feel confident and secure in her day-to-day. She may need space when she gets overwhelmed, and needs a person willing to give her that. 

Ruby is a wonderful dog for the right person, and we are determined to find her the right forever home.

Interested? Great! Submit and application at www.caninecastawaysrescue.org. The application approval process can take up to 7 business days. Once approved, we will contact you for that highly anticipated meet and greet.

Not ready to commit to being a full time fur mommy or daddy? You can apply to foster! Just fill out our foster application on our website, and be very thorough so we can match you with a great fit for you and your home!

animal.description:
Looking for a jogging or hiking partner?  Want a friend who loves the outdoors as much as you do?

Meet Charlie!  Charlie is a 1 yr. old handsome yellow Lab who just loves being outside and hanging out with any canine buddies that he can find.  Charlie came up from the south, and found a wonderful home, but it soon became apparent he needed another canine friend and lots of room to run.  He hated when he was left alone, but was reassured by a canine friend.

So Charlie is looking for an active couple or person who likes to walk, run, hike, camp, or just be outdoors -  he loves being outside more than in, so the more time he can spend enjoying the outdoors, the happier he is!  He loves other dogs, and gets along with a wide variety of personalities, but would do best with another active dog who enjoys playing.  He is also great on leash!

Charlie would not do well in a busy home with young kids – the noise and commotion would be too much for him.  He is tentative around new things, and takes time to adjust, so he needs someone who will be patient.  However, once he is comfortable, he will be your best buddy!  Charlie is a sweet boy, who is hoping to find his wonderful forever home!





PLEASE NOTE:  While this Lab may not be available for adoption by the time you complete the adoption process, other great Labs are always finding their way into our Rescue. 

For more information on this Lab, please contact INFO@BROOKLINELABRESCUE.ORG.  

If you are interested in adopting this Lab or any other Lab from our Rescue, please visit our Web site, www.brooklinelabrescue.org, for more information on our adoption process. If you need additional information about the adoption process or whether you are in our coverage area, please send an e-mail to our Rescue at info@brooklinelabrescue.org

Even if you are not ready to adopt, you can still help us help our Labs!

Brookline Labrador Retriever Rescue is a 501(c)3 non-profit volunteer organization funded entirely by donations. Donations are always needed to help with veterinary costs, transportation, and supplies for our dogs. For information on donating to BLRR please click here. Donations are accepted via PayPal or you can mail a check to: Brookline Labrador Retriever Rescue, P.O. Box 638, Warrington, PA 18976-0638

animal.description:
**Louie is currently staying in a foster home. If youd like to schedule a time to meet him, please contact Wayside Adoptions at (816)986-4426. Thanks!**
Hi there, Im Louie! Im such a good boy! Im friendly and affectionate and gentle and laidback. I want to be your best friend and hang out with you all the time. I feel like thats what I was put on this earth to do. So, I hope maybe youre looking for a low-maintenance friend just like me to welcome into your life. Im ready!
Im a darling, 9-year-old, 33-pound sweetheart with an expressive face and an unassuming, delightful personality. And Im already fully housebroken. Ive had quite a life. I originally came to Wayside about 4 years ago when a new baby arrived and made me nervous. I was then adopted by a nice family, but they brought me back to Wayside when they moved away and couldnt take me along. So now Im searching for a new family once again. Its scary to be alone, and the shelter can be a stressful place for a dog like me. Plus, it takes me a little extra time to warm up to new people. Thankfully, Ive been able to stay in a foster home as I wait for you to find me. My foster parents help me feel safe and special and loved. Ah, they are just what I needed.
Once in foster, it took me a few days to adjust and to learn to relax. My foster parents let me go at my own pace and they are patient and kind with me, gently praising me when Im a good boy, which is all the time. Ha! Im very well behaved in the house and I dont bother a thing. Foster Mom works from home, so someone is typically around, but I can be trusted to roam free in the house even when no one is home. At night, I sleep like a rock, soundly and quietly, on my dog bed in the bedroom. I dont make a peep all night. And I dont jump on the bed, even though I could. I never beg for food, Im quiet unless I need to alert the family that someone is at the door, Im content, happy, and such a nice friend. It fascinates me to watch the geese that gather outside our window. They provide me with entertainment! Sometimes I play with my toys too. Im initially wary when someone stops by, but I warm up with time. My favorite thing is to cuddle and bask in any attention you give me. In fact, I like to crawl up on Foster Dads lap to be as close as possible. We love to hang out together!
We have a fenced yard in my foster home, where I can play and explore, but I dont like to stay out for long. Im much more of a homebody and I dont need a lot of adventure or exercise to keep me happy. I do love going for leisurely daily walks though and Foster Dad says Im a joy to walk with. I dont pull on my leash and Im not reactive when I see other people or animals along the way. I live with another small dog in my foster home and we get along just fine together. We dont play much, but I enjoy his company. I will be happy to go home with another friendly, calm dog or perfectly content as your only dog as well. Young kids make me sort of nervous, so Ill need a home with kids over the age of at least 12. Im looking for a quiet and calm home without a lot of commotion.
I promise I wont ask for much and I wont cause any trouble at all. I just want to be with you, loving every single moment of our time together. Thats the life I dream of. Nothing fancy, but just a simple life filled with the love that comes from the bond of a dog and his person. Thats all I need.
Love, Louie
 ...

animal.description:
In addition to the following profile for this dog, please first read the Adoption Information at http://www.shihtzurescuemn.org/adopt.html to understand the process, requirements and timeline for adoption. An adoption application can also be found in the Adoption Info section. If, after reading that information, you have any questions, please submit your question via e-mail and it will be answered. Please do not request a phone call. A personal phone call will only be made when an adoption application has been submitted and the foster parent wishes to consider the application. Thank you!

Hello! My name is Ruby. I’m a very sweet and very shy 5-year-old female Shih Tzu. I have beautiful coloring and I weigh a healthy 11 pounds. I came to the rescue from a puppy mill, which was very harsh, isolated and lonely.  I’m still learning about the real world and everything in it. I’ve bonded closely with my foster mom, but I’m very cautious around other people. When I arrived in rescue, I had an eye injury, but it has since been treated and healed. I also have a chronic dry eye condition and will need prescription eye drops twice a day for the rest of my life. I love going outside, and potty training is going very well - although I haven’t quite adjusted to being on a leash. My favorite things are hanging out with my foster mom in her office or on the couch. I love bedtime - my tail wags and I get excited to be on the bed with my favorite blanket. I hope I can find a quiet home with patient, loving people who can continue to support me on my healing journey. My new family must meet the following requirements:

1. My new family must be experienced with dogs (ideally rescues) and commit to using positive reinforcement training methods, which may include seeking professional training, if necessary.
2. Be willing and financially able to care for my ongoing health needs (i.e. regular vet visits) and administer eye drops twice daily.
3. Must live within 30 miles of Plymouth, MN, so my foster parents can do a follow-up home visit.
4. I need a home where my people are around most of the time and will provide a positive, supportive environment.  I can’t be left alone for long periods of time.
5. I can share a home with other non-dominant small dogs and friendly cats.
6. Be physically able to lift me on/off furniture and up/down stairs (I haven’t quite learned how to do those yet).
7. Maintain my high quality dog-food diet (no human food). Sometimes it’s tough getting me to eat and drink - my foster mom can give you some tips.
8. I will run away when outside, so I require a secure, fenced-in yard or will need to always be on a leash when outside.  It’s best to secure the leash before you even open the door.
9. I am intimidated and wary of people both big and small, so only a quiet home with no young children will be considered.
10. Agree to attend the Shih Tzu Rescue Reunion held in September each year.

Ruby is spayed, current on vaccinations, microchipped, and on heartworm and flea/tick preventative.  Her adoption fee is $320.00 plus $24.08 sales tax for a total of $344.08.  


To meet Ruby, please complete an adoption application at the website listed in the first paragraph.  Due to COVID-19, we must take precautions regarding home visits.  The foster parent will discuss the home visit procedures with the applicant(s) once they are approved for that step of the adoption process.

animal.description:
Roxie is a 2 year old female GSP who is up for adoption. She has been quite perfect in the house!  She loves cuddling, she loves affection and she loves her food! She has never chewed anything in the house, and she has never had an accident in the house.  She uses the dog door to perfection and will go to her crate for her safe space.  She will play with the other dogs when everyone feels like it, and she has just been great in the house.  She has NOT been tested with cats, and likely will be fine with kids, although she hasn't been tested for them either. 
However....  

She needs a fenced in backyard.  She is terrified to go on walks or be out in "public" to say the least.  Her first reaction is to bolt, and run.  In fact, she was lost because she backed out of a harness and took off.  She was terrified, wouldn't come to anyone and we were fortunate to have an experienced trapper come in and trap her. Otherwise may still be on the run in the big city. 

You see, she lived in a kennel with very little interaction and socialization for a majority of her life.  She was isolated and wasn't taken places to learn about new things. 
So, now, everything is scary to her and her first reaction is to run. 

So whomever adopts her will have to be experienced and know how to handle such a dog.  Make no mistake about it, she is fantastic in the house, and just a wonderful pet, but her socialization is severely lacking.

animal.description:
Meet five-year-old and 24 pound Sampson from China. This poor guy was left abandon on the streets after his homeless owner left Beijing. Luckily a local rescue took him in and held him for the last four years. Due to his disability and being visually impaired he didn’t ever find a forever home. We were able to add him to a flight with other dogs we were already bringing. He’s a shy guy who is easy-going and doesn’t need much. He would do best in a patient experienced home. He is dog and cat friendly. He needs to learn English commands. He is a little bit overweight and would definitely benefit from daily exercise. We can’t even imagine what he has gone through even just to get to the United States. He is very sweet and just wants love and will make a great companion.

Thank you for reading about our awesome dog. All dogs came to us from different situations and we often do not know much about their past, but they are rescue dogs who deserve a second chance and need patience on their journey. All of our dogs our are in foster homes all across the bay area. 

The first step of the process is you must submit an application in order to set up a meet and great or talk with the foster family. Once application is submitted the foster parents will contact you to chat more about the dog and make sure they're a good fit and can answer any further question. The application answers most of all of our questions and can best match you. If you do not get the dog you apply for we can use your same application for 90 days towards another dog in our care and simply forward your app to that foster parent. 
http://form.jotform.com/underdogca/dog-adoption-application

All dogs will be fully vetted (Spay/ Neutered, Micro chipped, DHPP and Rabies Vaccinated) and other possible vet care prior to adoption.

The adoption fee is $350 which is considered a non refundable donation

visit us at underdogca.com or follow us on FB and IG @underdogca
https://www.facebook.com/underdogCA

animal.description:
Meet Lucy, this girl was surrendered with a dog named Morty after they recently lost their person. While Lucy and Morty are great friends, they are not overly bonded and don't need to be adopted together, they wouldn't be upset about either though! (Check out Morty's bio too!) Lucy is a bit on the shy side at first but once she gets to know you she is so so friendly and loves to be pet. She is just as soft to the touch as she looks and those eyes melt us every time.

Lucy is a spirited little thing, weighing in at only 30lbs. She loves playing with balls, dashing around in the snow, and doing her best to get you to dance around outside with her! It surprises us she is 5 years old, because she still is a puppy at heart. She likes to sleep at the foot of the bed and wake you up by nuzzling your ear and gently kissing your cheek, which to us is the best way to wake up!

Lucy is dog friendly, but needs a dog as friendly as she is. She is confident every dog wants her to kiss their face and clean their ears, and when they say no, she doesn't seem to get the hint. She is house trained.

Lucy is UTD on shots, preventative, micro-chipped, and spayed!

Lucy 's adoption fee is $250, and adopters must live within 175 miles of the Quad City Area.

If interested in meeting Lucy you must fill out the online application at www.k9kindnessrescue.org/adopt/application

Lucy and K9 Kindness Rescue thank you for considering adoption through rescue!

THIS DOG IS SLATED FOR EUTHANASIA by the County Shelter-- NEEDS IMMEDIATE FOSTER/ADOPTER.

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4512414.

Clancy is a big, fun loving dog that loves to play. He loves to play fetch and will drop his toy at your feet so you can throw it again and again. He will sit and wait for you to throw his toy or ball. He loves to play tug of war too. Unfortunately, he does it with his walking leash so Clancy would do much better walking if he has a harness. This big boy is also very treat motivated and will "sit" for his treats and take them gently.

Clancy is a young dog at only a year old and needs an adopter or rescue that can give him the basic training he needs. He needs to learn his manners when he's around other dogs. He's going to be a great, fun loving and playful dog to someone that can give him the type of home he needs. The shelter recommends that Clancy go to a home with older children. animal.description:
Animal Profile: Miller is an adorable 4 year old Chihuahua/Pug mix (best guess!) who will be joining us from California on January 17th. He is a happy, mellow little dude. We will post more info as we get to know him.

Seattle Foster Update:

Miller was shy upon his arrival, but after some time to settle in and decompress in his foster home, he is doing so well! His foster mom shares, "
His temperament is great, very cuddly and happy. He loves to be all up in your business, the closer the better. He still shows his belly when we approach and has demonstrated some nervous peeing if we move too quickly. He loves to play with his canine foster brother, especially chasing each other. He's more leery of our older dog, who is leery of him, but he's demonstrated no aggression at all with either dog. He's been doing great on leash! I'd describe his energy level as average, he likes to play but spends a lot of time happily sleeping as well. He has enthusiastically investigated every tiny hole in our fence so I think he could be an escape artist if allowed. Miller does great in his crate as well - he settles down and is quiet once he's in. Some light whining if he's in there too long, just when he's letting us know he needs to go potty. Overall, he's just a sweet and easy dog. And his curly tail is the CUTEST.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $475, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was rescued from euthanasia at a high-kill shelter in California and will be available for adoption in Seattle, once evaluated in a loving foster home in the greater Seattle area.

animal.description:
Adoption criteria for Georgie:

• Knowledge of and experience using advanced training techniques
• Experience working with high-drive herding breeds
• Ability to work the dog daily, providing intellectual as well as physical stimulation; reference given to people serious about training for a sport (herding, agility, flyball, etc.) or work (search and rescue, other scentwork,  etc.) 
• Securely fenced yard
• Human companion with dog most of the time, for life (after dog has adapted to new home, at most 2-3 hours per day alone) 
• Adults and teenagers only
• Residence within 150 miles of Felton, CA

Georgie is an intense, focused, drivey, 18-month-old, 40-pound, tricolor Border Collie.   She is intelligent, fast, agile, energetic, cuddly, affectionate, and in need of a mentally challenging job. She is a demon at fetch,  as currently all her intensity is focused on balls.  She is a dream for a handler looking for a dog to train up in any pursuit.  She is not suitable for inexperienced handlers or for people who want an easy family dog.  She is a working dog who must be presented with problem-solving challenges every day.  

Georgie is very social and playful.  She gets along well with other dogs who will tolerate her intensity, but she is much more interested in working in tandem with her person.  She sleeps peacefully with cats but if bored will attempt to herd them.  

Although she is extremely affectionate and cuddly with people she knows, Georgie displays some fear reactivity to new people, barking at them.  we have not seen any aggression or attempts to harm, but her handler will need to know how to counter-condition for this behavior.  Georgie was found running stray; she was filthy and matted and malnourished.  Her current caution is a normal and natural reaction to some bad times.  Anyone who throws a ball for her is granted her friendship immediately.  

Georgie is house trained and is nondestructive in the house.  She will sleep quietly in a large crate if her person is nearby, but she would much rather snuggle up next to her person's pillow.

Georgie has been spayed, has received core vaccinations and parasite prophylaxis, and has an implanted microchip.  

If you have been seeking an intense, loving, workaholic canine partner, and would like to assess whether Georgie is right for you, please write to

	Lynxcat@comcast.net

to request an application, or download from

 	http://www.paddingtonstation.us/available-animals.html

Only after your application has been approved can we set up an appointment for you to meet GEORGIE and her foster parents in FELTON, CA under strict COVID guidelines. 

We always answer email if we receive it. 
We never ship dogs.
Do NOT use the "Ask About" button -- enquiries made that way often do not reach us.

animal.description:
Leia is just as gorgeous as she is sweet! It’s very clear that this little girl was mistreated in the past, but she so desperately wants to leave that all behind and look ahead to brighter Colorado days!
Leia loves people, but it takes her a little time to warm up to strangers. Once Leia knows and trusts you, she will never leave your side and would prefer if you will simply sit and hug and pet her all the time. She is very playful and her favorite toy is her squeaky ball. She will toss it to herself and pounce on it and sleeps with it most nights. She is kennel trained and enjoys having her safe space to retreat to when things get to be too much. She takes a little longer to warm up to men, but is working on trusting all hoomans! She is still getting used to regular life things like traffic and encountering other people and dogs on walks, getting braver every day! She is pretty well behaved on walks overall! Leia is incredibly gentle and is not destructive. If something makes her nervous, she will move away and find a safe space until she gets more comfortable. She is curious and willing to overcome her hesitations with a little patience and time!
She is learning basic commands and once she learns them, she enjoys pleasing people with her new tricks. Leia is also 100% potty trained! She is very silly and loves to watch TV, especially when there are other animals on screen.
Leia needs a loving and patient home that can give her time to acclimate and help push her gently to explore new things. She could be in a home with children, but preferably older children that have a deep understanding of dog behaviors and are willing to give Leia lots of space. We are currently looking for a home without any other dogs or cats until we know how this princess does with other animals - she deserves ALL the loving anyway.

animal.description:
This goofy guy is Roscoe and he is a 4-6 year old Redbone Coonhound mix who weighs around 50 pounds! He came to us as a stray back in November and he was underweight and missing 75% of the fur on his body due to a severe flea allergy. (The picture with the green grass was taken a week or so after we got him in and he had already had a few medicated baths.) After a few months of proper flea treatment and medicated baths we are happy to report that his fur has grown back wonderfully and he has put on several pounds! 

Roscoe is a playful dog and loves to run around in he yard swinging his rope toy or begging on of the workers to play tug of war with him! He will also chase tennis balls but is better at keep away than fetch. He also loves chewing on Nylabones and carrying them around with him wherever he goes! He does also love to "talk" to people in the true hound fashion.  
Roscoe does get really excited when he meets new people and does jump up so we are working on the down command and he seems to be picking it up quickly! He also knows how to sit and is very food/treat motivated which will help with the rest of his training! Because he came in as a stray we do not know if Roscoe is housetrained but he does really well in his kennel overnight with only the occasional accident. 

We believe Roscoe would do well in a home with children who are 10 and older as he is still working on the down command and may knock smaller children over without meaning to. We have not had the opportunity to test him with cats but he did do really well with out senior Pit bull (Belle) when we had them together. We can absolutely test him with cats if a prospective home needs us to do so and he will need to meet any dog(s) in a prospective home to make sure everyone gets along. 
Due to Roscoe's severe flea allergy he does have to be kept on NexGard oral flea prevention year round for the rest of his life. This is something that most dog owners due (at least through the Spring and Summer) anyway but we wanted to make sure any prospective adopter is aware that this will be necessary to keep Roscoe in the optimal health. 

If you would like to set up a time to come meet Roscoe please give us a call at 641-774-5113 as we are open by appointment only.

If you would like to donate towards Roscoe's care please go to the top of this page and click on the Sponsor button. You will then be redirected to his Petfinder Sponsor/Donation page. Any amount is greatly appreciated!

Roscoe's adoption fee is $75.00 and that does include all of his Vet work.

Hi! My name is Jawbreaker, but my friends call me “JB.” I am the sweetest boy, but sadly someone in my past broke my jaw and I have spent the last few months healing.  I am all better now and totally not focused on my past! I am still a young guy, and although I am an adult, I am basically an overgrown puppy! My exuberance for life is high!! I love other dogs and cats and people and all the things. My walks take awhile because I always want to say hi to everyone.  I am learning my manners and basic commands, and truly just love life. I need a fun, active family who will continue my training! 

ADOPTION FEE: $200 (All MVPC dogs are heartworm-tested, completely vetted, spayed/neutered, microchipped, crate-trained and house-trained).

A $100 hold fee is required for approved applications and will be applied to the full adoption fee at the time of the home visit. 

ADOPTER: Dog experience 
BIRTHDAY: Estimated 18mo
FENCE: Required (an electric fence is not an acceptable form of containment)
DOGS: Yes
CATS: Yes
KIDS: Yes, over 5 please 

INQUIRIES: ALL inquiries begin with a submitted adoption application, which is found on our website, www.miamivalleypitcrew.com. We do not adopt to individuals under the age of 25. We prefer male/female dog pairings unless both already reside in the home. 

DO NOT: USE THE PETFINDER CONTACT/ADOPT BUTTONS--we are unable to monitor those and you will not receive a response. 

PLEASE NOTE: We are volunteer based and a home visit is required; we have a two-hour adoption radius from Kettering, OH for our adult dogs and 75 miles for our puppies. animal.description:
If you are interested in this dog, don't waste time with an inquiry! Fill out an application here to get the ball rolling...
https://pethavenmn.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/dog-adoption-application/

Here is more about Kato!

12-year-old, 70-pound Boxer/Retriever mix
House-Trained: Yes
Crate-Trained: Yes, however she is well-behaved when left to roam 

Kato came to Pet Haven after spending two and a half years in a shelter. She is an absolutely lovely gal who displays what her foster mom calls “resting scary face” when she looks alert. But behind that stare is all sweetness and love. Her goofy personality has shone through since being in her foster home! 

And do not let Kato’s age fool you! She loves to jog and sprints across the backyard in her quest to chase off squirrels and enjoys daily walks. She is very smart and learned sit and down and been wonderful on leash while in foster care. When she is not on walks, chasing fauna in the yard, learning tricks, or eating, she loves to take long naps. 

We are sorry to say that she thinks cats are for chasing and has shown reactivity towards other dogs who do not ignore her and needs to be in a pet-free home. After two years in the shelter though, we think she has earned having a monopoly on all of the attention and belly rubs anyway!

Kato would love to find a forever home with a fenced backyard where she can stretch her legs and patrol for squirrels. Her forever home should also continue to work on her with building up confidence and slow, controlled socialization. And most of all, lots of love and affection!

Check out this sweetheart on Instagram: katothewonderpup


Her adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ FULLY BEFORE SUBMITTING AN APPLICATION:

It took 13 days for him to even come near people. 21 days for him to be able to go out and come in without being carried. Another 11 days before he would just follow his foster outside and go to the bathroom in less than an hour... and back inside without standing by the door barking for a half hour. 60 days into our journey and he sits calm in the tub while getting a bath and all0ws you to clean his paws. Every morning we're up by 6 and we spend an hour outside...practicing 'touch', hiding and seeking treats, getting used to new sounds and new things. He doesn't hesitate by the doorway at all, he usually happily follows his foster right out and happily follows her back in and he does his business mostly within 15 minutes. He does have setbacks now and then and most recently, it took over 4 hours of being out with him to get him in. Bisou needs someone with a flexible schedule who can work with him if he has setbacks. He loves his treats. He's amazing with all other dogs, big and small and would do best in a home with another dog. For having zero socialization its astonishing he's come so far. He's one of the most gentle dogs ever, and he's one of the goofiest. When he runs he runs sideways in this awkward gallop. The first time he saw his reflection in the sliding glass doors he tried to stick his head through the closed door to see 'the other guy'. When he's groomed shorter he almost looks white. When his coat is a little longer you can see the gorgeous apricot color that melts into the white and fawn. He is as gorgeous inside as he is out. He'll make the most loyal companion for the right person(s). It may not take 60 days the next time....or it may. But I can tell you this...it will be the best 60 days. He may adapt or he may not and may revert to old behaviors. Bisou will need patience and an experienced pet parent(s) who won't force progress on him, rather take his que as to what feels comfortable. That means building trust...and building trust takes time... A fenced yard is an absolute must. Loud noises and quick movements still scare him. As such we don't recommend a home with small/young children. As he's coming out of his shell he can get excited and jumpy. He's crate trained but not fully housetrained yet. He's working on it. We feel Bisou would do best in a home with another dog.

Bisou is neutered, up to date on vaccines and microchipped. He's about 15 months old.. Local adopters only as we need to be able to support any training needs and multiple meetings.

Bisou is a very special, very beautiful work in progress. Please only apply if you are fully committed and meet all of the criteria above.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
=========================================================

Please contact
app@aarfhouston.org
for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .

Puppies
that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations.

Children under 8 years old
often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.

Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue!

The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.
